<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bragman: ''I did the right thing''  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Former Assembly Majority Leader Michael
Bragman said a failed attempt to oust Speaker Sheldon Silver
doesn't mean he made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did the right thing,'' the Syracuse-area Democrat insisted
Tuesday. ''I don't care what the result is. This was a conscious
decision on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman resolution challenging state Assembly Speaker Silver's
leadership was defeated by the chamber Monday, but he said that was
''just the beginning'' of reform. Critics have complained that
Silver's method of doing business was autocratic and secretive, and
Bragman said he intends to change that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every revolution has to start some place. We've started the
revolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said he plans to meet with his supporters in the newly
formed Democratic Majority Reform Caucus to discuss plans for
establishing reforms laid out in the groups' statement of
principles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to come back and talk about how we bring
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will also not be dissuaded by any retaliatory moves from
Silver, he added. Bragman lost his leadership post last week, which
carried a $34,500-a-year stipend, and with it went his Capitol
office and some staff.
</P>
<P>
   He is also certain to be evicted from the majority leader's
office in the Legislative Office Building. Bragman's successor has
not yet been selected by Silver and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't care if I'm in a broom closet,'' Bragman said. ''I'm
here because the majority wants change. We're going to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman said that he continued to be a ''friend'' to state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall, who became a central figure in the coup
attempt, if only in Bragman's mind. Bragman said he ''thought we
had a partnership'' with McCall that would include McCall using his
considerable influence with black state Assembly Democrats to help
Bragman against Silver.
</P>
<P>
   But McCall, the only black elected to statewide office in New
York, insisted that he viewed the Bragman-Silver dispute as a
matter only for Assembly Democrats and said he did no lobbying for
Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Carl and I need to talk,'' Bragman said on Albany
radio station WROW-AM on Tuesday. ''I need to know if he wants me
to support his gubernatorial bid. He and I will talk about the
whole past week and we'll go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman was an early backer of McCall for governor in 2002. The
other most likely candidate at this point is HUD Secretary Andrew
Cuomo, whom had been considered close to Silver.
</P>
<P>
   The McCall-Cuomo competition for governor grew to be one of the
bones of contention between Bragman and Silver.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman has been in the Assembly for 20 years. He hinted Tuesday
that he intends to seek re-election in November, but added that he
will discuss his political future with his family and constituents
first before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have any reason for not being here,'' he said. ''This
is far from over.''
</P>
<P>
   As of January, Bragman reported having about $943,000 in his
campaign account -- a huge amount for a state legislator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
