<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver: I'm guilty of being a 'nice guy'  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A challenge to his job beaten back, Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver says his chamber's Democrats should come
together and put a week of intraparty strife behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Silver appeared before reporters Tuesday for the first time
since ex-majority leader Michael Bragman's challenge for speaker
emerged last week to say a ''time for healing'' had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to call many of the 19 dissident Democrats
who voted against him on Monday when the challenge to his position
formally failed on the floor of the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said Bragman's move against him was ''four years in the
making'' and that he probably should have heeded other members'
warnings about the ambitions of the ex-majority leader on his job.
</P>
<P>
   ''While other people have said it to me over and over again
during the four years, I chose not to believe it,'' Silver said.
''In hindsight, I am guilty of one thing, probably being an
optimist and a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though calling for party unity, Silver was anything but contrite
Tuesday as he appeared surrounded by more than 50 Democratic
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is stronger from what he called the ''family feud''
involving Bragman ''because we cut the cancer out of the leadership
team'' in the Assembly. Silver fired Bragman as majority leader
after he went public with his challenge to the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Very few of the dissidents supporting Bragman have
''legitimate'' concerns about how he has run the Assembly, Silver
contended. They included complaints that Silver is distant and hard
for members to see, that his staff controls the flow of legislation
and negotiations with the Senate and governor and that
rank-and-file members are shut out from meaningful participation in
the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The Bragman supporters have issued a ''statement of principles''
calling on Democrats in the Assembly to reform the way they run the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   But Silver gave only vague answers to reporters' questions about
whether he would adopt reforms to give members more of a voice in
the operation of the Assembly. ''Criticism is always valid in
context,'' he said at one point Tuesday. Silver said later that
Democrats would rule in a ''more open fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his Democrats would look at the dissidents' proposed
reforms to ''make a determination as to which, if any, of those
items have some credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was not willing to acknowledge if the battle with Bragman
had convinced him to change his leadership style in any way.
</P>
<P>
   ''It obviously always gives you cause for introspection,'' he
said, ''always, both in terms of who you trust and who you don't
trust. How you operate. How you communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   A Silver supporter, Richard Brodsky of Westchester County, said
the speaker was not weakened by the overthrow attempt, and that
Bragman's coup had nothing to do with reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about the statement of principles,'' Brodsky said.
''Those have to be looked at. There may be something there that has
value to us. We're going to make that decision ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver himself said that using the words ''reform'' and
''Bragman'' together is an ''oxymoron.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver denied a frequent charge by Bragman in the past week,
that Silver and his allies had extorted support from dozens of
members by threatening their committee chairmenships or to ruin
them at the polls later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''No sir,'' he said. ''Me or any member of my staff did not call
or threaten anybody in this house.''
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, who also talked to reporters Tuesday, replied that,
''The members know that what I say is true.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver also said Bragman's contention that lobbyists formulate
legislation in the Assembly was ''unequivocally not true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
