<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oneidas, counties seek to renew land claim talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- The Oneida Indian Nation and Madison and
Oneida counties want to take one more stab at settling the tribe's
long-standing land claim out of court.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Monday with U.S. District Court Judge Neal
McCurn, the tribe and counties said they would like to continue
negotiations rather than have the judge declare an impasse and
schedule the land claim for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Oneida Nation remains committed to settling this land
claim through negotiations and wants to continue that process,''
tribal spokesman Mark Emery said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the two counties also see negotiations as the best
alternative, they said in confidential status reports filed with
McCurn, who pushed back his filing deadline several times in hopes
that the two sides would resume formal talks.
</P>
<P>
   New York state also would like to resume negotiations, but only
if the Oneidas are earnest about reaching a settlement, said
Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been down this path before only to be disappointed by
their insistence of linking the land claim to gaming issues,''
McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas have said it was the state that has brought gaming
issues into the talks, seeking to secure a share of the profits
from the Oneidas' Turning Stone casino in Verona.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas, who now live in New York, Wisconsin and Canada, are
seeking compensation for 250,000 acres in Madison and Oneida
counties they claim the state purchased illegally in the late 18th
and early 19th centuries. Yearlong negotiations broke off April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Emery said Tuesday the nation had made ''additional constructive
ideas'' to the judge intended to help settle the land claim. He
would not elaborate on what those ideas were.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a settlement, the counties have insisted the
1,100-member Oneida Indian Nation of New York pay property taxes
and collect sales taxes from non-Indians who purchase goods on
reservation land. The counties have also demanded the Oneidas limit
reservation land to 25,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The Oneidas have offered to pay the counties $20 million, in the
form of $1 million each year for 20 years, to offset sales taxes
they say sovereign Indian nations do not have to collect. They also
have offered to set aside $25 million of the settlement money for
the counties to offset unpaid property taxes and limit their
reservation to 40,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   The 14,000-member Oneida Nation in Wisconsin told the judge they
see no point in continuing negotiations if the New York Oneidas and
the counties cannot compromise. The Wisconsin Oneidas have no
differences of opinion with the counties, said Arlinda Locklear,
their lawyer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
