<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB investigators prepare to remove plane wreckage for closer study </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER NEWTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- Crash investigators retrieved the
engines and propeller assemblies Tuesday from a plane that crashed
on a remote mountainside over the weekend and prepared to send them
to the factories for closer examination.
</P>
<P>
   A team of forensic investigators also arrived from across the
country to help identify the remains of the 19 people killed in
Sunday's crash.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board officials hired
construction workers to lay thousands of pounds of gravel atop a
rain-soaked dirt road that snakes near the site of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The recovery vehicles made their way up the winding roads,
through miles of thick forests of northeastern Pennsylvania late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The study of the engines is something we want to do at the
manufacturers' assembly plant. They have the tools,'' NTSB
investigator Frank Hilldrup said Tuesday night. ''No disassembly
will occur at the hangar where we are storing the parts until
delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   The engines are bound for a Honeywell plant in Phoenix, Hilldrup
said. The cockpit voice recorder box, which officials say did not
record any sound, is to be sent to a Fairchild Inc. plant in
Florida. Hilldrup said he did not know where the propellers would
be sent.
</P>
<P>
   An official tape of a conversation between pilots and the
control tower is headed to Washington for analysis by NTSB sound
experts, as well as a recording made by a teen-age aviation buff
who was listening to a police scanner at the time of the crash. The
sound analysis could reveal background noises on the plane that
could provide more clues, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hilldrup said he did not know how long it would take for the
last of the wreckage to be removed from the crash site, ending the
on-site investigation. He said a final NTSB report could take up to
a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday morning, the Executive Airlines twin-engine
turboprop crashed in the rain 9 miles south of the
Wilkes-Barre/Scranton International Airport. It was carrying
passengers home from a gambling trip to Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A tape recording of a final conversation between air traffic
controllers and the two pilots on the plane has emerged as the
primary source of information about what happened just before the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots declared an emergency soon after missing their first
approach of an airport runway. The plane rose to 4,000 feet
immediately after the first approach. Just before the second
approach, the pilots said they had lost both engines.
</P>
<P>
   Early analysis of radar indicates the plane veered to the south,
NTSB officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers began providing information about the
terrain and elevation after radar indicated the plane was flying at
about 2,000 feet above sea level, considerably lower than the
minimum safe altitude, Hilldrup said. The crash site was 1,765 feet
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers suggested that they were near several
highways and other areas that might have worked as a landing zone,
including the northeast extension of the Pennsylvania Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB officials believe the plane crashed moments later. They
said they have no evidence that the plane was attempting to land.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that air traffic controllers lost the plane on
radar nearly three tenths of a mile from where it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Painting a more complete picture of the accident could be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   An early analysis of the cockpit voice recorder box revealed
that the tape had been erased, but it was unclear when that
happened, Hilldrup said. Executive Airlines policy required
recorders to be tested on the first flight of every day, he said.
The NTSB said earlier that the recorder might have failed to
operate because of an improper power supply.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know at this point whether the box was ever
operational on this plane during past flights,'' NTSB member George
Black said. ''That is something we are looking into.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was also without another piece of equipment
investigators said might have provided valuable clues -- a flight
data recorder. That device records such data as the plane's speed
and altitude. Such a recorder is not required for the model of
airplane that crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also plan a careful inspection of the fuel system
and a reconstruction of the electrical system. On Monday,
investigators tested fuel from the truck that had last fueled the
plane and confirmed that it was uncontaminated. Efforts to test
fuel traces at the crash site were inconclusive as of Tuesday
night, Hilldrup said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not optimistic that we're going to get anything from
(fuel analysis),'' Hilldrup said. ''The fact of the fire and the
intensity of the fire means that we don't have much of a sample.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, members of the Disaster Mortuary Operations Response
Team were setting up a mortuary in an airport hangar at the
Wilkes-Barre/Scranton airport Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have yet to release the names of the victims, but
various news organizations were able to confirm some of the
identities Tuesday. Officials said the names would be released as
each is positively identified.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Transportation Safety Board:
http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
