<HEADLINE> Thumbnails of the dead in the Wilkes-Barre plane crash  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A thumbnail look at some of the 19 people killed in
Sunday's
plane crash near Wilkes-Barre, Pa.:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Donna Barbini Cali, in her 40s, of Dunmore, Pa. A community
volunteer and the mother of two sons, Colby and Cameron, ages 12
and 9. Married to Dunmore lawyer Brian Cali. Was taking her mother,
Florence Erhardt, on the trip to celebrate Erhardt's upcoming
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   --Florence Erhardt, 73, of Honesdale, Pa. She is survived by her
husband Leonard and daughter, Barbara, of Mexico. Had worked in the
Wayne County Courthouse and as a bookkeeper at an auto dealership.
</P>
<P>
   --Nancy Maleski, 66, of Moosic, Pa. Homemaker, retired garment
factory worker. Died along with daughter Elaine Pilosi. Survived by
husband of 47 years, Henry; daughters Debra Maleski of
Schnecksville, Pa. and Patricia Maleski of Nutley, N.J.; son Paul,
a Pennsylvania state trooper in Dunmore; and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   --Elaine Pilosi, 46, of Old Forge, Pa. A day care administrator
at Wee Care Day Care Center in Blakely, Pa., for the past 13 years.
Was planning next year to celebrate the weddings of sons Christian,
27, and James, 26. Took her father's place on the flight when he
backed out a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   --Bernard Kachinko Sr., a Larksville, Pa., paving contractor in
his early 60s. Was apparently traveling alone. Survived by his
wife, four children and several grandchildren. Described as a
loving father in a tight-knit family. His two sons work in the
family paving business; one of them, Bernie, is the volleyball
coach at King's College in Wilkes-Barre.
</P>
<P>
   --Bob Supatoski, a retired trucker in his early 60s, and his
wife, Lillian, a secretary at the Gertrude Hawk Chocolates Co. in
Dunmore, Pa. The couple lived in their Scranton, Pa., neighborhood
for 28 years, and are survived by one daughter, Robin.
</P>
<P>
   --Gerald and Sharon Decker of Fleetville, and his brother,
Eugene, of Dalton. The two men ran a contracting business. Gerald
and Sharon Decker, who were in their 50s, are survived by two sons,
David and Gerry. Sharon Decker, a homemaker, was a lively woman who
was fun to be around, a friend said. Her husband was an avid
hunter. Eugene Decker is survived by at least one son, Russell.
</P>
<P>
   --Joan E. Kunkle, a widow, lived in Wilkes-Barre and sung in the
choir of the First Welsh Presbyterian Church. She was 63.
</P>
<P>
   --Frances M. Appel, 73, was a retired bakery worker. She lived in
a high-rise apartment complex called Plains Manor near
Wilkes-Barre.
</P>
<P>
   --Wayne Frantz, no age available. He was an accountant and lived
in Hawley, Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
