<HEADLINE> Settlement reached in I-95 crash lawsuit  </HEADLINE>
jlbcfls1dr1
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDIA, Pa. (AP) -- A settlement was reached Tuesday only hours
after a trial began in the state's civil lawsuit against a New
Jersey company whose truck caused a fiery explosion on Interstate
95 on Memorial Day weekend 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Connolly, a spokesman for Attorney General Mike Fisher,
said the settlement reimburses the state for the entire $2.95
million it spent repairing the I-95 bridge in Chester that was
destroyed when a gasoline-filled tanker truck careened over the
concrete median of I-95 in Chester, sideswiped a bus, struck a
pickup truck and exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Both truck drivers were killed and a section of I-95 was closed
for five months after the May 23, 1998, crash.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement came after opening statements and testimony by
two witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The state will not receive punitive damages from Samuel
Coraluzzo Co. of Vineland, N.J., or any admission of fault by the
company. The firm rejected the state's charge that it violated
federal trucker-rest regulations, contributing to the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
