<HEADLINE> Poll: Ruling Party Leads in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By LISA J. ADAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An independent poll Tuesday showed the
presidential candidate from Mexico's ruling party significantly
ahead of an upstart opposition campaign that could be the most
serious electoral threat to Mexico's establishment in 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   The ACNielsen poll conducted for the daily newspaper Milenio was
the latest in several weeks of varying results by different polling
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting undecided voters, Institutional Revolutionary Party
candidate Francisco Labastida was favored by 42.9 percent, while
Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action Party was preferred
by 35.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Two major recent polls had shown Fox ahead, although in both
cases the difference was within the margin of error. Fox has
recently been surging in the polls after starting out well behind
Labastida, whose party, known as the PRI, has held the presidency
since 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, of the leftist Democratic Revolution Party,
followed in third place in the poll published Tuesday with 17.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted from May 13-19 and interviewed 2,005
likely voters in urban and rural locations, Milenio said. The
margin of error was 2.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the three candidates met Tuesday at Cardenas'
campaign headquarters and agreed on a nationally broadcast debate
Friday -- but only after an acrimonious squabble over Fox's proposal
that the three accept one network's offer to hold the debate
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Fox charged that the other candidates' insistence on a delay
showed they were the ones putting up obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would show up Friday, he said, ''I haven't taken the
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the decision to talk did not come easily. It came after
three days of public squabbling and televised mini-debates in which
Labastida and Fox accused each other of lying, attacked each
other's records and blamed the other for causing the debate to
collapse. Cardenas, meanwhile, compared both Labastida and Fox to
reviled former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida accused Fox of being afraid to debate because of the
latest poll, which seemed to reverse a recent trend showing Fox
pulling even and even moving ahead. Fox said polls had nothing to
do with the candidates' disagreements over the debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
