<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentalists argue Millstone cases in state Supreme Court  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court is considering
the allegations of environmentalist who claim the Millstone nuclear
power reactors are polluting Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest court heard Tuesday from lawyers
representing plant-operator Northeast Utilities and environmental
groups including Fish Unlimited. There is no deadline for the
justices to rule.
</P>
<P>
   The high court took from the Appellate Court three cases in
which the groups allege that the reactors emit illegal pollution
into the sound and harm the fishery.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we claim in those cases is bad faith and collusion
between the (Department of Environmental Protection) and Northeast
Utilities,'' said Nancy Burton, the attorney for Fish Unlimited and
other groups from Connecticut and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But NU spokesman Joe Pillittere said the case is not really
about environmental concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've stated repeatedly that their sole goal is to shut down
Millstone,'' he said. ''Our goal is really to be the best of the
best both in terms of operation and environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The first case involves a 1998 settlement between NU and the DEP
over alleged violations of Millstone's water discharge permit. The
$1.2 million settlement included a $700,000 fine and a $500,000
donation to environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
   Fish Unlimited claims the penalty was not high enough and
amounts to collusion between NU and the DEP. Burton also said it
has done nothing to stop future environmental abuses.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant Attorney General Richard Webb said it was among
the highest monetary settlements of any such case. He also said
that environmental programs implemented since the settlement have
''directly enhanced the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   NU attorney Elizabeth Barton said it was a ''significant
settlement,'' adding that the trial judge called it ''tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   The second appeal dealt with allegations that the Millstone Unit
2 cooling system is damaging winter flounder in Niantic Bay and
Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit by Fish Unlimited sought to shut down the plant until
a cooling system was installed that would recirculate water from
the sound instead of drawing in fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   NU has said that its nuclear plant cooling systems have a
negligible impact on the fish population. A Hartford Superior Court
judge last year blamed overfishing for the drop in numbers of fish.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Burton said, a DEP official has agreed with a
report from a winter flounder expert from Rhode Island who blamed
Millstone for the problem. The trial judge failed a year ago to
allow rebuttal from that expert, Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   The third appeal involves claims that the DEP issued an improper
wastewater discharge permit to the Millstone complex. The groups
argued that the permit was invalid since the complex was idled for
months because of safety concerns. NU has said it has the proper
permits.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who said she was optimistic after Tuesday's session,
called it a historic day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the first time the Supreme Court has set aside its whole
morning on an issue regarding environmental grievances and
Millstone,'' she said. ''Nobody has ever challenged Northeast
Utilities' right to operate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 0101 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000524.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expos 3, Giants 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Rondell White homered and went 4-for-4, and
the Montreal Expos defeated the San Francisco Giants 3-2 on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vidro had three hits for the second consecutive game as the
Expos won their fourth straight.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Bonds homered and doubled twice for the Giants, who lost
for the ninth time in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pavano (5-1) allowed two runs on seven hits in six-plus
innings for the victory. Dustin Hermanson recorded the final four
outs for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Rueter (2-3) gave up three runs on nine hits in seven
innings. He has not won in his last five starts dating to April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Vidro now has 22 multihit games, including eight with three
hits. He's batting .522 (24-for-46) since May 11, with eight
doubles, three homers and 13 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   White had his first four-hit game of the season and extended his
hitting streak to 10 games. He's hitting .419 (18-for-43) during
that span with six doubles and four homers. White's .359
(70-for-195) career average against the Giants is his best against
any team.
</P>
<P>
   White's seventh homer of the season gave the Expos a 2-0 lead
after Vidro singled in the first. White hit the first pitch from
Rueter over the 404-foot sign in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Cabrera added his fourth homer of the year to put
Montreal ahead 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds' 17th homer, in the fourth, cleared the right-field stands
and bounced off the boardwalk before splashing into McCovey Cove.
Bonds also doubled home a run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Giants SS Rich Aurilia was ejected by umpire Greg Gibson
for arguing balls and strikes in the fourth. He became the second
Giants player (Jeff Kent) to be ejected this season. ... Vidro and
White were a combined 4-for-19 (.211) against Rueter entering the
game. ... The Expos are 12-3 in the first game of a series. ... The
Giants were 1-for-9 with runners in scoring position on Tuesday.
They entered the game hitting .301 in those situations.
</P>
