<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Otter Wins Bid in Idaho  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT TANNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four-term Lt. Gov. Butch Otter won his bid Tuesday to succeed
ultraconservative GOP Rep. Helen Chenoweth-Hage, while Arkansas
Democrats hoping to challenge embattled GOP Rep. Jay Dickey went to
a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever won Idaho's GOP primary was heavily favored to win the
fall election. With more than half the precincts reporting, Otter
took nearly twice as many votes as Dennis Mansfield, who founded
the religious right group Idaho Family Forum with Chenoweth-Hage.
</P>
<P>
   With 59 percent of precincts reporting, Otter, a millionaire
businessman, won with 49 percent, or 24,195 votes, to Mansfield's
25 percent, or 12,499. The two led a field of eight Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky also held congressional primaries, and all three states
had presidential contests made meaningless because Al Gore and
George W. Bush have already wrapped up their parties' nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republican leaders backed Otter in an election campaign
that focused on who would inherit Chenoweth-Hage's conservative
mantle. Though she did not endorse anyone, she did not object to a
national term limits organization's ads linking her politics to
Mansfield's.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield, who focused on social and moral issues, is a staunch
opponent of abortion. Otter opposes abortion but says he takes a
more libertarian approach that keeps government out of people's
lives, and prefers to talk about land rights issues and gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   The winner will face Democrat Linda Pall, a Moscow City Council
member, and candidates from the Libertarian and Reform parties.
</P>
<P>
   Chenoweth-Hage, who fulfilled a campaign pledge to retire after
three terms, built her career on her opposition to big government
and what she called environmental extremism. Her remarks after the
1995 Oklahoma City bombing were viewed as sympathetic to the
militia. She also once claimed that minorities don't like northern
Idaho because it's too cold.
</P>
<P>
   In President Clinton's home state, the crowded field ensured a
June 13 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With 96 percent of precincts in Arkansas reporting, state Sen.
Mike Ross was the leading vote-getter, with 44 percent, or 39,182
votes. Second-place was less clear: former TV reporter Dewayne
Graham had 23 percent and 20,556 votes, while former state Rep.
Judy Smith, who lost to Dickey in 1998, had 22 percent and 19,610
votes. A fourth candidate got 12 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a runoff, the winner had to get more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   None of the candidates hoping to challenge Dickey made his vote
for impeachment an issue, though Dickey said he expected it to come
up in the campaign. GOP Rep. Asa Hutchinson -- one of the House
prosecutors in Clinton's trial -- faced no opposition from either
party.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey is seeking his fifth term in the traditionally Democratic
district, which includes Clinton's hometowns of Hope and Hot
Springs. Dickey, who has no Republican opposition, was criticized
this year after he told black farmers he could do little for their
efforts to seek federal help for discrimination because they didn't
support him politically. He later mended fences with one group of
farmers who recently endorsed him.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, state Rep. Eleanor Jordan defeated two lesser-known
candidates to win the Democratic nomination to challenge two-term
GOP Rep. Anne Northup in a district that is 2-1 Democratic. Jordan,
the only black woman in the state Legislature, hopes to become
Kentucky's first black member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Northup had no opposition in the primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 0121 </TRAILER>
