<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Celebrate Israel's Withdrawal  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arabs are celebrating what they view as a
victory over Israel, though some worry that Israel's withdrawal
from south Lebanon happened so quickly it threatens stability.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli pullout from land it has invaded twice and occupied
since 1982 marked the first time Israel withdrew from Arab land
without negotiating a settlement -- a situation that makes the event
more chaotic -- but to many, far sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a clear sign that determination and will can lead to
the liberation of an occupied homeland,'' said Abu Ahmed Fouad of
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical PLO
faction opposed to the peace accords with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the Lebanese guerrilla group that led the effort to
drive Israel out, was widely praised throughout the Arab world
Tuesday. In the past, Arab nations have supported Hezbollah's goals
but distanced themselves from it, trying to avoid quarrels with a
U.S. government that considers Hezbollah a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   Syria should ''borrow Hezbollah for the Golan, or set up its
own. It will cut the long negotiations short for them,'' said Fouad
al-Hashem, a columnist for Kuwait's Al-Watan daily.
</P>
<P>
   The peace talks between Israel and Syria -- the main power in
Lebanon -- that were aimed at eventually returning most or all of
the Golan Heights to Syria have been stalled since January.
</P>
<P>
   Damascus state-run radio called the withdrawal a ''sound defeat
to Israel'' and credited the ''cohesion between Syria, Lebanon and
the heroic (Lebanese) resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel started pulling its troops from southern Lebanon six
weeks ahead of its July 7 deadline and rushed to finish the
withdrawal after the rapid collapse of its militia ally, the South
Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian negotiator Yasser Abed Rabbo said the pullout
''proves that occupation, no matter how long it lasts, will end'' --
referring to Israel's 33-year presence in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
   On behalf of the 22-member Arab League, the group's Assistant
Secretary-General Saeed Kamal said: ''We congratulate Lebanon and
the Lebanese people for this historic achievement by forcing out
occupation forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Amr Moussa of Egypt, the first Arab nation to
sign a peace deal with Israel, said the withdrawal was a necessity
and the ''faster it is carried out the better.'' If the situation
remains tense too long, it will hurt the peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait University political science professor Massouma
al-Mubarak, however, warned in an article in Al-Siyassah newspaper
that the ''sudden pullout will certainly upset Lebanese security
arrangements.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been fears that an Israeli withdrawal in the absence
of a peace agreement with Syria would result in bloody retaliation
by guerrillas seeking vengeance on those who allied with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Daghestani, a member of the Saudi Consultative Council,
called on Lebanon's government to take control.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Lebanese government should make sure that the situation in
the south remains calm now that Israel is leaving -- and make sure
that the Lebanese people there do not turn on each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 0152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000524.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Refugees Move Smoothly  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KFAR AMNUN, Israel (AP) -- Israeli-allied militiamen fleeing the
chaos of Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon are being greeted by
orderly bureaucrats who register them by computer for housing, ID
cards and health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army may have miscalculated how quickly the
militiamen would flee Lebanon, but the Jewish state -- which has
absorbed hundreds of thousands of immigrants -- is already preparing
to teach them Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 refugees, members of the South Lebanon Army and their
families, crossed into Israel on Tuesday, fearing retaliation by
Hezbollah guerrillas who are taking over a border zone the militia
and Israeli troops patrolled for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In less than three days, the 2,500-member SLA disintegrated,
some fighters fleeing to Israel, others surrendering to Lebanese
authorities and a few remaining to defend their villages. Those who
made it to this makeshift transit camp in an idyllic resort on the
Sea of Galilee bitterly criticized Israel for the tumult.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli army withdrew from there and left us inside,''
said an exhausted 24-year-old militia member who fled after
Hezbollah captured the outpost he was defending. He would not give
his name for fear of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the refugees, many of whom know Israel from jobs or
vacations there, reluctantly resigned themselves to their new home.
Some planned to seek refuge in a third country. Almost all harbored
dreams of returning to their villages.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, which until this week had publicly given only vague
promises about the militiamen's future, expects up to 10,000
refugees -- many of them Christians who fear revenge attacks from
the Shiite Muslim Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Buses streamed into the transit camp Tuesday, unloading refugees
who lined up inside a tent to be photographed, receive an ID card
and register for health insurance and Social Security. Each was
given a name tag with a picture of an Israeli flag and a Lebanese
cedar, the SLA symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Education Minister Yossi Sarid said the adults would be
offered Hebrew classes and the children would be registered in
schools by September. In the meantime, he said, he would set up
summer camps.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has successfully processed waves of Jewish immigrants
fleeing violence in their home countries, but SLA refugees may find
it particularly difficult to readjust.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Israeli Arab villages, long-time opponents of
Israel's occupation of Lebanon, have said they don't want the
newcomers living in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Word had already spread in the transit camp, and many refugees
said they preferred to live in Jewish towns.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees know that unless Israel can make peace with Syria,
the real power in Lebanon, they will likely never return home.
Israeli-Syrian peace talks broke down in January.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has promised to deliver militiamen who surrender to
the Lebanese authorities, but the refugees -- many of whom have been
sentenced to death or long jail terms in absentia -- do not trust
the Lebanese government, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
