<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alaska Air Tapes To Be Released  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN HUGHES
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the crash investigation ongoing, federal
officials are letting the public hear what the pilots of an Alaska
Airlines plane were saying to air traffic controllers just before
their jet plunged into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 261 was en route from Puerto Villarta, Mexico, to San
Francisco when it crashed north of Los Angeles on Jan. 31, killing
all 88 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration plans to release a roughly
2-hour-and-40-minute tape at 10 a.m. EDT. The agency is not
expected to comment because the National Transportation Safety
Board still is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   According to federal authorities, Flight 261 was three hours
into its four-hour journey when the pilots of the MD-83 made a
routine check with Los Angeles air traffic controllers at 3:15 p.m.
and were cleared to 31,000 feet. Then, 15 minutes later, the crew
radioed they were having control difficulties and started
descending.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:15 p.m., the pilots reported a problem with the horizontal
stabilizer, a tail part that controls the plane's up-and-down
motion, but said they thought they could land at Los Angeles.
During further exchanges, Flight 261 requested clearance for a
lower altitude, which was given.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:17 p.m., the flight was advised to contact another air
traffic controller on a different frequency; that transmission was
not acknowledged. Four minutes later, the plane went off radar
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Following the crash, the government ordered inspections of more
than 1,100 planes in the MD-80, MD-90, DC-9 and Boeing 717 series
following the crash. Airlines replaced jackscrew devices in the
tail sections of 18 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators have been closely examining the stabilizer
jackscrew, a long, threaded piece of metal that turns to move
through a stationary nut.
</P>
<P>
   The jackscrew from the crashed plane had a stripped nut, and the
screw itself carried metal shards of the same material as the nut.
There also were impact marks on the nut, and the board is trying to
determine if the impact marks and stripping occurred before the
plane crashed or afterward or was caused when the plane hit the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Aviation Administration: http://www.faa.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
