<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marine's Remains Bring Healing  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) -- Two weeks after the official end of the
Vietnam War, Lance Cpl. Andres Garcia jumped on a helicopter bound
for the Cambodian island of Koh Tang to settle some unfinished
business.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old known as ''Andy'' was among about 200 U.S.
Marines sent by President Gerald Ford on a daring mission to rescue
the 39 American crewmen of the merchant ship Mayaguez, which had
been captured by Khmer Rouge patrol boats.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia -- like the other Marines -- was unaware that the U.S.
crewmen already had been released by the Cambodian communists.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen U.S. servicemen, including Garcia, were killed or lost
when their helicopter was hit by a rocket from Khmer Rouge troops.
Five others also died or were missing after the Mayaguez Incident
on May 15, 1975. They were the last American combat casualties in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, Garcia's remains have been identified
and will be brought back to his hometown in southeastern New
Mexico. A ceremony was scheduled today.
</P>
<P>
   ''People say it's like opening a wound again,'' says Garcia's
brother, Alberto 47, his eyes filled with tears. ''And I say no,
it's finally going to close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Garcia family got word just two months ago about the
positive identification. Until then, sister Sara G. Neff and some
other relatives held out hope that Garcia could be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of us were in denial, albeit it was a very small chance,''
said Neff, 39, who joined the U.S. Navy in her brother's honor. ''I
didn't accept that he was gone until this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon recently has been able to identify the remains of
Garcia and five others through DNA analysis. The remains had been
recovered over the past several years and brought to an Army
laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Pentagon released the names of three more: Lance
Cpl. Gregory S. Copenhaver of Port Deposit, Md.; Pfc. Walter Boyd
of Norfolk, Va.; and Pfc. Kelton R. Turner of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   For the Garcias, the return of the remains of their son means
they finally will have a place to visit him. Some, like Neff, have
run their fingers across his name on the Vietnam War memorial wall.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia has been memorialized in many ways over the years: Three
children have been named for him. His mother and eight siblings
wear silver wristbands in his honor. And brother Alberto has
planted a pear tree in his backyard, symbolizing the times when
they playfully took fruit from a neighbor's tree as children.
</P>
<P>
   All the family has wanted is to have Garcia home.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a good surprise and a sad surprise,'' said sister
Margaret Ornelas, 50. ''This is what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For more on the Mayaguez Incident:
</P>
<P>
   SpecialOperations.com:
http://specialoperations.com/Operations/mayaguez.html
</P>
<P>
   USMC/Vietnam Helicopter Association:
http://www.popasmoke.com/kia/750515/notforgotten.html
</P>
