<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Readies For Artillery Drill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan said Wednesday that China's
military will hold live-fire artillery exercises this week near
outlying Taiwanese islands. The drills will be routine and not
threatening, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the Taiwanese military has been quick to report
any Chinese actions that might cause public panic as this island
begins a new era of relations with its longtime rival -- a period
that could bring greater possibility of war.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Taiwanese military said China would hold
artillery exercises from Thursday to May 31 in Fujian Province's
Quanzhou Bay and Shenlu Bay in southeast China.
</P>
<P>
   The military said the routine drills are held every year and
pose no threat to Taiwan, which has control over several small
islands off Fujian's coast.
</P>
<P>
   China and Taiwan separated amid civil war in 1949, and Beijing
has repeatedly threatened to invade. Relations have been especially
sensitive since a new democratically elected government took office
in Taiwan last week.
</P>
<P>
   It is still uncertain whether relations will improve or become
more tense during Taiwanese President Chen Shui-bian's four-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, local and Hong Kong media have caused public panic
and drops in the Taiwanese stock market with reports of threatening
Chinese military displays. Many of these reports have been based on
unfounded rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's military seems to be trying to head off such reports by
immediately sharing information it has collected from its close
monitoring of the mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
