<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Watch Blowout Game Video  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- On the day after their worst loss of the
season, the Los Angeles Lakers were forced to watch video of the
debacle -- a horror movie with an unhappy ending.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland Trail Blazers, knowing they don't play again until
Friday, got the day off Tuesday, confident and riding the momentum
of Monday night's 106-77 blowout in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   With the best-of-seven Western Conference finals tied 1-1, the
Lakers find themselves in a position that's been too familiar in
the playoffs for a team that won 67 regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   As Lakers guard Ron Harper noted in the Phoenix series, Los
Angeles seems to lack the killer instinct.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the same old thing for us, trying to find a way to get
ourselves up and ready to play, in an attack mode,'' Los Angeles
coach Phil Jackson said after the video session at the Lakers'
practice facility in El Segundo.
</P>
<P>
   A player who once brought that attack attitude for Jackson's
Chicago Bulls, Scottie Pippen, set the tone for Monday night's
victory with his relentless drives to the basket and harassing
defense.
</P>
<P>
   He and Rasheed Wallace, among others, frustrated Shaquille
O'Neal with double- and triple-teams all night.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've got three strong, long guys doubling me,'' O'Neal
said. ''In Game 1, we lived by the jump shot. In Game 2, we died by
the jump shot. We really didn't get good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday, the Lakers had won 24 of 25 at home, with the
only defeat a meaningless one in a game that O'Neal missed just
after the team had clinched the homecourt advantage throughout the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now that advantage has been lost to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tip, Pippen took it to the Lakers. In the first
half, he repeatedly drove to the basket, where he either scored or
was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mind set was to attack,'' he said, ''to establish that we
weren't going to be a jump-shooting team.''
</P>
<P>
   From his days in Chicago, Pippen knows Jackson's triangle
offense as well as any player in the series, and the Blazers
stifled Los Angeles as no team has all season.
</P>
<P>
   ''You try to defend the penetration as much as you can --
basically take it away from a passing standpoint,'' Pippen said.
''We were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had 21 points, 10 rebounds and three steals. Wallace had
career playoff-highs of 29 points and 12 rebounds. And Steve Smith
scored 24 points, twice as many as Kobe Bryant, and scored 11 in
the decisive 20-0 run in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was 2-for-15 from the field in the quarter and was
outrebounded 14-5. For the game, the Blazers dominated the boards
49-34.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding Dunleavy's unsuccessful
''Hack-a-Shaq'' tactics in Game 1 was forgotten in the magnitude of
Los Angeles' loss. There was no need to repeat the incessant
intentional fouling of the big guy, who still provided a good
argument for Dunleavy's Game 1 strategy by going 5-for-17 at the
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' vulnerability has been on display before in the
playoffs -- in two losses in Sacramento, in a one-point victory over
Phoenix in Los Angeles and in a one-sided loss in Phoenix. But the
Lakers weren't just vulnerable Monday night, they were awful.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've still got three days to practice and get ourselves ready
to go up to Portland. ''We're really respectful of who Portland is
as a basketball team. We know we're going to have to go up there
and play well. We've done that,'' Jackson said, referring to the
Lakers' 90-87 victory at Portland on Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are 1-3 on the road in the playoffs. The Blazers are
5-0 at home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Garden will be rocking. Will the Lakers be reeling from
that 29-point loss, or will they have recovered from any emotional
hangover?
</P>
<P>
   ''Put it behind you,'' Bryant said. ''That's all. I don't care
if we lost by one, 20 or 40. The series is still tied 1-1.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
