<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actors Union Probes NFL Stars  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE GOLDBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 9, Keyshawn Johnson and Eddie George reportedly shot a
commercial for Adidas. On May 10, the NFL Players Union told its
players to honor an actors' strike and not make commercials.
</P>
<P>
   That could make moot an investigation into Johnson, George and
John Lynch that could lead to punitive action by the Screen Actors
Guild.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told our guys one thing -- don't do it,'' Gene Upshaw,
executive director of the NFL Players Association, said of his
action supporting the striking actors.
</P>
<P>
   But Upshaw's memo to executive board members and player
representatives wasn't sent until nine days after the strike began
on May 1. Since this is the offseason, it took awhile for the memo
to trickle down to the rank-and-file, although George is a member
of the union board.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, traded last month from the New York Jets to Tampa Bay,
is the highest-profile player involved and seems to be SAG's main
target, although what the sanctions against him might be aren't
clear -- fines are the most usual. SAG has acknowledged that
Johnson's representatives have told its investigators that the wide
receiver wasn't aware of the strike when he made the commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Upshaw said that his union -- like those for basketball and
baseball players -- fully supports the SAG strike. It also is
supported by Tiger Woods, who says he won't do any commercials
until the labor dispute is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Upshaw said he didn't know the three players took part in the
commercial shoots.
</P>
<P>
   In his memo, Upshaw noted that the actors had been on strike
''for a couple of weeks now.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Because many of you are involved with or represent companies
desiring to use your image and services in commercials, we are
urging you to avoid shooting commercials or advertisements that are
considered 'struck work' until further notice,'' Upshaw wrote.
</P>
<P>
   '''Struck work' includes both TV and radio ads on the local and
national level. ... I am asking for your participation in endorsing
this cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Another target for the Screen Actors Guild is retired Gen. Colin
Powell, who is involved in the non-union production of a public
service announcement for the retired general's youth charity.
</P>
<P>
   The spot for America's Promise, The Alliance For Youth, began
filming in Maryland on Sunday, and SAG is picketing the production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
