<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m.EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, May 24, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arabs Celebrate Israel's Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Arabs are celebrating what they view as a victory over
Israel, though some worry that Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon happened
so quickly it threatens stability. The Israeli pullout from land it has invaded
twice and occupied since 1982 marked the first time Israel withdrew from Arab
land without negotiating a settlement -- a situation that makes the event more
chaotic -- but to many, far sweeter. Hezbollah, the Lebanese guerrilla group
that led the effort to drive Israel out, was widely praised throughout the Arab
world Tuesday. In the past, Arab nations have supported Hezbollah's goals but
distanced themselves from it.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
United Owner Buying US Airways
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The owner of United Airlines, ranked No. 1 in the world,
has agreed to buy US Airways, which is the world's 10th-largest, according to a
source familiar with the talks. The boards of both UAL Corp. and US Airways
Group Inc. have approved the deal, the source said on condition of anonymity.
The combination will create an airline behemoth with 6,500 flights a day and
hubs on both coasts; in contrast, the world's No. 2 carrier, American Airlines,
offers but 3,600 daily flights. Details of the acquisition were not immediately
known, but the Wall Street Journal reported on its Web site Tuesday, citing
sources familiar with the deal, that UAL Corp. will pay $4.3 billion in cash and
assume $7.3 billion in debt and long-term leases.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft, DOJ Head Back To Court
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of back-and-forth volleying between
Microsoft Corp. and the government, the question of what sanctions should be
imposed against the software giant now shifts to the federal judge who has
overseen the antitrust case from its start. U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson is trying to craft a remedy that will curb Microsoft's future behavior
and restore competition in the software industry. The Justice Department, along
with 17 of the 19 states, has urged Jackson in legal documents to split
Microsoft into two companies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Momentum Picking Up on China Trade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters of a measure to normalize trade relations with
China claimed to have seized the momentum as both sides of the issue dueled for
a dwindling pool of undecided lawmakers. A showdown vote was scheduled today in
the House. The Clinton administration and business lobbyists worked behind the
scenes to line up the votes needed for passage. The bill would extend permanent
normal trade relations to China, guaranteeing China the same low-tariff access
to U.S. markets that nearly every other country in the world has. For the past
20 years, China has received this benefit, but only after an annual
congressional vote.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Ruling Party Leads in Mexico
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An independent poll Tuesday showed the presidential
candidate from Mexico's ruling party significantly ahead of an upstart
opposition campaign that could be the most serious electoral threat to Mexico's
establishment in 71 years. The ACNielsen poll conducted for the daily newspaper
Milenio was the latest in several weeks of varying results by different polling
agencies. Discounting undecided voters, Institutional Revolutionary Party
candidate Francisco Labastida was favored by 42.9 percent, while Vicente Fox of
the center-right National Action Party was preferred by 35.8 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'Millionaire' Shows Some Weakness
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Television's seemingly indestructible force, "Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire," finally showed some cracks in the armor last week. The ABC
ratings juggernaut was trounced Thursday by the season finale of "Frasier." The
NBC sitcom, which is moving to Tuesday nights in the fall, had 33.7 million
viewers compared to the 18.6 million viewers for "Millionaire." Against more
lackluster competition, "Millionaire" bounced back to 27.7 million viewers, just
200,000 fewer than its Sunday night average for the year. Two competing movies
-- "Growing Up Brady" on NBC and "The Linda McCartney Story" on CBS -- did
poorly.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Wednesday morning for the sixth consecutive
session, pushed down by further losses on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 172.52
points to 16,146.21 at the end of the morning session. In New York on Tuesday,
the Nasdaq fell 199.66 to 3,164.55. The Dow Jones industrial average ended down
120.28 at 10,422.27.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds Beat Dodgers 3-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. and Barry Larkin homered as as the
Cincinnati Reds ended the Los Angeles Dodgers' six-game winning streak with a
3-1 victory Tuesday night. Osvaldo Fernandez (1-0), who made his major league
debut with San Francisco nine months after defecting from Cuba in July 1995,
allowed three hits, struck out four and was pulled after a leadoff walk to
pinch-hitter F.P.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
