<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Shanghai Noon'  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two days after the dust and bombast of ''Mission: Impossible 2''
settle, another action flick high-kicks its way into theaters
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It's risky business to open a fast-paced adventure yarn the same
weekend as Tom Cruise returns with the Impossible Missions Force.
With Jackie Chan's ''Shanghai Noon,'' however, Disney figured it
had a winner. The studio is banking that its comic western can tag
along on Cruise's coattails as ''M:I2'' fires the starter's pistol
(and other artillery) to officially launch Hollywood's busy summer
season.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move. ''Shanghai Noon'' is a merry romp that will help
wash away the taste of last summer's six-shooter fiasco ''Wild Wild
West.''
</P>
<P>
   In this one, the ancient East meets the Old West. Chan plays
Chon Wang, a palace guard in China's Forbidden City who comes to
America in the late 1800s to rescue a kidnapped princess (Lucy
Liu).
</P>
<P>
   Chon hooks up with a new-age, image-conscious train robber, Roy
O'Bannon (Owen Wilson), who's more adept at shooting off his mouth
than his pearl-handled pistols. Roy also is more interested in the
chest of gold coins sent as ransom than in helping to free the
princess.
</P>
<P>
   The mix makes for a very amusing interracial buddy flick. Roy
mistakes his new partner's name as John Wayne and pronounces it a
terrible moniker for a cowboy. He laments that when the two become
wanted men, his ''sidekick'' Chon gets a $1,000 reward posted,
while Roy gets just $500. Roy also envies the cool nickname Chon
picks up, the ''Shanghai kid.''
</P>
<P>
   When they land behind bars, Chon suggests that one of them feign
illness so they can jump their jailer.
</P>
<P>
   ''You mean the sick prisoner routine?'' Roy asks. ''Does that
still work in China? 'Cause it's really been done to death here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Shanghai Noon'' relies on Chan's usual ballet of wild
martial-arts stunts as he chops up cops and robbers and cowboys and
Indians. The high-octane action is nicely choreographed and prompts
Roy to boast of his own skills as a lethal weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know karate, but I know crazy, and I will use it,''
Roy tells a bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Chan makes for a hilariously likable Western hero, and there's
good turns from Liu as the socially liberal princess, Roger Yuan
and Xander Berkeley as scowling villains and rodeo star Brandon
Merrill as Chon's smirkingly stoic Sioux bride.
</P>
<P>
   It's Wilson, though, who rounds up the laughs. Best known as one
of the oilmen-astronauts in ''Armageddon'' and a ghost-hunter in
''The Haunting,'' Wilson breaks out in ''Shanghai Noon'' with a
marvelous comic take on a goodhearted bandit who's less concerned
with booty than how he looks and acts while he's stealing it.
</P>
<P>
   After the pyrotechnics of ''Mission: Impossible 2'' whet
Memorial Day picnickers' appetites for action, ''Shanghai Noon''
makes for a nice, low-tech dessert.
</P>
<P>
   ''Shanghai Noon,'' distributed by Disney, is rated PG-13 and
runs 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
