<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fatal fire that killed boys is linked to kitchen appliance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PITTSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- A quick-spreading fire that killed two
brothers started with an electrical problem in a refrigerator,
according to the Rensselaer County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the boys and their mother were spending the
night at the Rensselaer County house, which homeowner Kathleen
Seror realized was burning after a fire alarm woke her up Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the thorough on-scene investigation and critique of the
various events, we feel very strongly it was caused by an
electrical problem with the refrigerator on the first floor,'' said
Sheriff Daniel Keating.
</P>
<P>
   After attempting to extinguish the fire with a pan of water,
Seror ran next door to call 911. Her husband, David Seror, ran
upstairs to rouse the guests, who escaped by jumping out the second
floor window.
</P>
<P>
   A head count outside the building revealed that David Trudell
Jr., 7, and Jacob Trudell, 6, were still inside.
</P>
<P>
   By then the house was totally engulfed, preventing further
rescue efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
