<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus driver indicted in fatal collision with pedestrian  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) -- A bus driver has been charged second-degree
manslaughter in the death of a Cornell University student who he
allegedly ran down in March while under the influence of marijuana
and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Stranger, 37, of Ithaca, was indicted Tuesday by a
Tompkins County grand jury. Stranger remained free. He was to be
arraigned at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also charged Stranger with second-degree
vehicular manslaughter, second-degree assault and various drug and
motor vehicle violations. If convicted of second-degree
manslaughter, the most serious charge, Stranger could receive up to
15 years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Police said 21-year-old Michelle Evans was killed March 16 as
she walked near a campus intersection. The indictment alleged that
Stranger drank within six hours of going on duty that day and also
was drinking and smoking marijuana while on duty. Police
confiscated six empty beer bottles from the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Stranger, originally charged with driving under the influence of
alcohol, was fired from his job with Tompkins Consolidated Area
Transit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 0842 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000524.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 34; Nasdaq Climbs 6  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average is up 34 points
in today's early going. Advancing issues on the New York Stock
Exchange hold a 4-3 lead over decliners.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Composite Index is ahead six points and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 Stock Index is up six points.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts expect to see some bargain-hunting today,
fueled by today's big merger in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers tend to put investors in a positive mood, although it
remains in question whether United's deal for U.S. Airways will
generate much enthusiasm outside of that sector.
</P>
<P>
   Most overseas market averages have been lower today after
yesterday's sharp losses on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq yesterday posted its tenth largest percentage loss on
record.
</P>
</TEXT>
