<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Occidental to close two facilities  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) -- Occidental Chemical Corp., moving to
focus on its core business, will shut down its Chemical
Intermediates Group in Niagara Falls and Grand Island Technology
Center, eliminating 340 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''After careful analysis, we have concluded that chemical
intermediates no longer meet our strategic objectives,'' J. Roger
Hirl, president and chief executive, said Tuesday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is one of the biggest economic blows the struggling
city of Niagara Falls has suffered in a decade, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is devastating,'' Joseph Marino, president of the United
Way of Niagara, told The Buffalo News. ''These people are the
blue-collar force of this city, and their quality of life will be
affected tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Chemical intermediates, chloro/fluorotoluene products, which are
sold to the agricultural and pharmaceutical industries, were recent
introductions to OxyChem operations, whose core business is
chlorine and caustic soda, vinyls and performance products.
Ironically, the bulk of recent capital investments at the Niagara
Falls facility were related to building the new product portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe (chemical intermediates) are better suited to
companies that are already firmly established in these businesses
or who have unique needs which can be met through direct
manufacturing,'' Hirl said.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said buyers would be sought for the Niagara
Falls plant and several related businesses and assets and that
discussions were already under way. However, he said, the company
will begin closing the plant while sales opportunities are
explored.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Texas-based division of Occidental Petroleum
Corp. will not affect operations at OxyChem's two other Niagara
Falls manufacturing facilities, which employ another 580 workers,
or the company's plants in nearby Fort Erie and Niagara Falls,
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives met with the affected workers Tuesday and
explained a phased plan to end production and research. An OxyChem
spokesman declined to release details, including when operations
would cease.
</P>
<P>
   ''They called us all into the lunchroom, sat us down and
bludgeoned us with the news,'' said worker Doug Hess. ''It was just
last year they invested $200 million in this plant. We thought we
were safe. And now this. We're all in a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   The Niagara Falls plant, with 255 workers, produced 335,000 tons
of chlorine and 371,000 tons of caustic soda in 1999 along with the
soon-to-be-eliminated intermediate chemicals. The plant has its
roots in the Hooker Electrochemical Company that was established at
the site in 1906. Hooker was acquired by Occidental in 1968 and
renamed Occidental Chemical in 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 0952 </TRAILER>
