<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 48; Dow Up 28  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed at the start of trading today
as technology shares dragged the Nasdaq composite index lower for a
sixth straight day. A big merger in the airline industry sparked
some buying.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was down 47.76 at 3,116.79.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 28.44 at 10,450.71, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 0.67 at 1,373.19.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares remained mired in a slump. JDS Uniphase fell
4[ to 75 and Amazon.com fell 3 11/16 to 43. The technology sector
has borne the brunt of investors' worries over rising rates, which
are expected to cut into corporate profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have determined that technology stocks, still
among the most expensive issues on the market, are too expensive
given the weakening outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways soared 23~ to 50 3/16. UAL Corp., the parent company
of United Airlines, is buying US Airways for $4.3 billion in cash,
the companies confirmed today. In addition to the cash payment, UAL
will assume $7.3 billion in debt and aircraft operating leases.
That heavy debt load pared UAL shares by 9 5/16 to 51 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 131 million shares,
ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 5.62 to 453.39.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.7 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was down 1.0 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
