<HEADLINE> Dow Up 57; Nasdaq Down 23  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks rose today as investors sought
stable investments while technology stocks remain mired in a slump.
A big merger in the airline industry sparked some buying.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 57.22 at 10,479.49, and the Nasdaq composite index
was down 23.09 at 3,141.46.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 3.99 at 1,377.85.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares dragged the Nasdaq lower for a sixth
consecutive session, although some scattered bargain-hunting was
preventing the index from repeating the sharp drops it suffered
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   JDS Uniphase fell 1{ to 77| and Amazon.com fell 2 5/16 to 44].
The technology sector has borne the brunt of investors' worries
over rising rates, which are expected to cut into corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have determined that technology stocks, still
among the most expensive issues on the market, are too highly
priced given the weakening outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a bear market in technology,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp. ''What worries me is that
it's beginning to look like more than just a valuation problem.
Investors are now wondering if earnings estimates for tech
companies are too high at a time when interest rates are going
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   US Airways soared 21 3/16 to 47[. UAL, the parent company of
United Airlines, is buying US Airways for $4.3 billion in cash, the
companies confirmed today. In addition to the cash payment, UAL
will assume $7.3 billion in debt and aircraft operating leases.
That heavy debt load pared UAL shares by 9 5/16 to 51 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, news of the merger enlivened the rest of the airline
sector. For the most part, shares of regional airlines that are
also seen as takeover targets rose. Alaska Air rose 2~ to 31 7/16
and KLM Airlines rose 2 5/16 to 22 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Larger airlines that are perceived as potential buyers slipped.
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, fell 4 1/16 to 28 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 348.72 million
shares, well ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 6.38 to 452.63.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
