<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews  </HEADLINE>
Audio reviews from The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selected new releases:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''Love and Basketball'' (Overbook Music/New Line Records) --
Various Artists
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack to this romantic hoops flick is just as sweet and
soulful as the film itself. The movie, about a couple whose
romantic life takes as many bounces as their respective basketball
careers, is divided into four quarters, as viewers watch the pair
grow up from their childhood in the 1980s to today.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack has no such time formula: It randomly switches
back and forth from old school jams to neo-soul offerings, but does
it in such a way that the result is a natural flow from such
artists as Angie Stone (who does a smoldering remake of the Simply
Red tune ''Holding Back the Years'') to Rufus featuring Chaka Khan,
to the always fierce Me'Shell NdegeOcello.
</P>
<P>
   Besides conjuring up old memories, the oldies but goodies are
guaranteed to get you grooving again, because their magic is
timeless. Even if ''It Takes Two'' from Rob Base and DJ EZ Rock
does sound dated, it's still one of the all-time rap grooves that
will make anyone want to get up and dance. And who can resist
rocking to the voice of Al Green on the old jam ''Love and
Happiness?''
</P>
<P>
   Just as these tunes stand the test of time, a few of the new
offerings position themselves to be future classics. The standout
is the sexy track ''Dance Tonight'' from Lucy Pearl, the new group
that includes former Tony Toni Tone member Raphael Saadiq and ex-En
Vogue songstress Dawn Robinson. The song fits perfectly with this
soundtrack because it borrows its sound from the past -- the '70s --
to come up with a fun summer groove that will hook you from the
opening note.
</P>
<P>
   --By Nekesa Mumbi Moody, Associated Press Writer
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''WYSIWYG (What You See Is What You Get)'' (Republic/Universal)
-- Chumbawamba
</P>
<P>
   While Chumbawamba's breakthrough smash, ''Tubthumping,''
reverberates in sports arenas and pubs worldwide, the activist
music collective from Leeds, England, rewires with ''WYSIWYG (What
You See Is What You Get),'' an album of tracks woven together like
a memorial quilt.
</P>
<P>
   An array of musical styles morphs from song to song as
Chumbawamba revels in satirical critique of the American psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Chumbawamba meditates upon the Internet's dichotomy of community
and isolation in ''Pass It Along'' (''Pass it along by word of
mouse; Pass it along, don't leave the house''). The civil unrest of
Woodstock III and the World Trade Organization protests is
reinforced in ''I'm Not Sorry, I Was Having Fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The band sends up the NRA on ''Moses with a Gun,'' while the
bombastic ''Jesus in Vegas'' recycles celebrity for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Chumbawamba even gives a nod to the Bee Gees via Martin Carthy
in the nearly a cappella version of the somber ''New York Mining
Disaster 1941.''
</P>
<P>
   -- By J.W. Lim, Associated Press Writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 1202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000524.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Band Puts Its All Into Making It  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- The boys in the band take to the
darkened stage amid thick cigarette smoke and the smell of stale
beer.
</P>
<P>
   They are following in the footsteps of legends who played here
at the LKA Longhorn, a dank, dark warehouse at the edge of this
German industrial city -- legends like Metallica. Alice Cooper.
AC/DC.
</P>
<P>
   There are other footsteps, too -- those who came aiming for
stardom and now are forgotten, except for some old concert posters
wallpapering the building.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, industry analysts estimate, more than 1,000 bands
are signed to recording deals. Fewer than 1 percent ever find fame.
Their fate turns on talent, radio play, promotions, tours -- and
luck.
</P>
<P>
   The band at LKA Longhorn is known as Simon Says, a punk rock
band with heavy metal leanings. They've reached the Billboard 100
and are on the edge of blowing up or blowing out.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was like, 'Now or never,''' says guitarist Zac Diebels.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   In Stuttgart, the audience is loud. The music is louder.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are Simon Says from Sacramento, California,'' screams
singer Matt Franks into the microphone to thunderous applause.
</P>
<P>
   This is Day 20 of a month-long tour by bus with German
powerhouse band Such A Surge and newcomers Flow Fy.
</P>
<P>
   The bands sleep by day. They play by night. They share buses.
</P>
<P>
   On this tour, there are no ''Limousines and Penthouse Suites'' --
a track from Simon Says' yet-unnamed upcoming album.
</P>
<P>
   Most days, the guys don't know where they are or where they are
going. Recounting stories from the road, they have to look at all
their access badges, which list cities and dates.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's Monday, it must be, what? Another German city,''
cracks Diebels, 23.
</P>
<P>
   Their bus rolls through Munich, Berlin and other cities, but the
only sites the band sees are the parking lots of concert venues.
The tour is about getting exposure, band members say.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, they look every bit the stereotypical rockers
with their T-shirts, jeans, dyed hair, tattooed arms and pierced
ears. In one case, a pierced tongue.
</P>
<P>
   But each personality plays a distinct role in building the band.
</P>
<P>
   Diebels is the salesman, pitching the band to industry types and
the media. Once a college student with aspirations of being a
Capitol Hill lobbyist, he is articulate and relentless in his
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Mike Johnston, 23, plays the devil's advocate, always
taking the other side in discussions -- just to make sure all their
options are represented. Twenty-two-year-old Franks prefers to take
the middle road. And bass player Mike Arrieta is the band's
listener. The youngest of the four, at 20, he interjects something
only when he feels it's absolutely needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of all the years I've known Mike he's been like that. Where I
use a thousand words to say 10, he uses just five,'' Diebels says.
</P>
<P>
   The quartet began, like many groups, as a garage band -- teen-age
friends pounding out notes and playing covers of their favorite
songs. Almost from the beginning in 1993, Diebels, Franks and
Johnston were writing and performing their own songs. They were
joined nearly three years later by Arrieta.
</P>
<P>
   They were kids having fun, even taking their name -- Simon Says --
from the child's game.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little childlike about their music -- aggressive
power chords, ear-shattering drum mixes and solid, sometimes
soulful, lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ''It started out as something to do and then it became this
thing that we couldn't imagine not doing,'' Diebels says.
</P>
<P>
   They took self-promotion seriously to get their music out to the
public, attacking utility poles and bulletin boards with staple
guns and flyers, spending hundreds of dollars on postage and even
more on telephone bills. They began booking high schools, and
playing to lunchtime crowds by day and clubs by nights.
</P>
<P>
   On a shoestring budget, they released two albums on a local
independent label.
</P>
<P>
   They earned a cult following, rave reviews from the rock
underground and precious local radio air play.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1998, Simon Says was making so much noise, record
labels started to listen. They signed with Hollywood Records to a
seven-year, three-album contract. The producer of the first was Rob
Cavallo, who helped engineer Green Day's smash debut album
''Dookie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood Records 12-track debut ''Jump Start'' has
experienced a modicum of success. One of its singles was slapped
onto the ''Varsity Blues'' movie soundtrack, which hit the
Billboard top-selling albums list.
</P>
<P>
   A second song, ''Slider,'' was put in MTV's new artists
rotation, and a third, ''Life Jacket,'' slowly wound its way up the
Billboard rock chart.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the group started a yearlong tour in cargo vans
of more than 200 high schools and nightclubs, stopping at hotels
only to shower. Halfway through the tour, they got an unexpected
break as the opening act for hard rock's Filter, which was on the
Billboard Top 10 and traveling in luxury buses.
</P>
<P>
   But while Simon Says was putting everything into their
aggressive, in-your-face performances, with songs exploring the
dark corners of their lives, Disney-owned Hollywood Records put
them on the music-video rotation on the Disney Channel. ''Life
Jacket,'' a personal song about their experiences in music, was
sandwiched between the likes of Britney Spears and 98 Degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hollywood was working for them. I think they saw it as an
opportunity for them and tried it. But they aren't a boy band. They
are a hard-rocking group of guys, accomplished musicians,'' said
Kylee Brooks, a disc jockey who gave the group unlimited radio air
play on one of Northern California's leading rock stations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought it was going to be easy for them. ... The
appeal of Simon Says is their live show. To get them, you have to
see them and then listen to the album,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a point emphasized by their Stuttgart show -- it's sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those attending never heard of the group. But they leave
with armloads of T-shirts and copies of the CD.
</P>
<P>
   On a balcony overlooking the sales table, Arrieta coaches
potential buyers under his breath. ''Come on. You want the T-shirt.
Buy it,'' he whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the cramped bus, the guys go over their performance with
a couple of friends who have joined them for the final leg of the
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Success is measured in part by audience participation: stage
diving, crowd surfing and slam dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, the band played in the east German town of
Cottbus, a place struggling economically after reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ''They just stood there. It was really strange,'' Diebels said.
''This show was great compared to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the band's formation, weekly meetings and performance
critiques have been part of their work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched bands self-destruct over ego, alcohol and drugs,
Simon Says follows a code of sorts: No drinking the night of a
show; no frontman; no making decisions about the band's future
without the others; and absolutely no ego toward other band
members.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have attitude about what we do, about what we do on
stage,'' says Johnston. ''But we can't have an attitude with each
other. Occasionally, one of us is full of it, but there are three
other people to call us on it.''
</P>
<P>
   To make their rules work, the four share a two-story,
five-bedroom house on the outskirts of Sacramento. They also
collectively share the responsibility and the rewards for writing
and composing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in this together,'' Diebels says.
</P>
<P>
   Even the telephone answering-machine message makes the point:
''You've reached the Simon Says house. Leave a message.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Day 21 of the tour, Simon Says hits Frankfurt's
Batschkapp, a music hall for more than 30 years. The stage is
small. But Franks makes space himself -- crowd surfing. Hand over
hand he's passed from one end of the club to the other, still
clutching the microphone and never skipping a lyric. At the same
time, audience members jump the barricade, climb onto the stage
and, with a running start, jump back into the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston takes to the drums like a maniac. He puts on his own
show, reminiscent of the early days of Motley Crue's Tommy Lee.
Diebels and Arrieta are a team on stage with combined riffs that
echo in the tiny music hall.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience, Thomas Schwartz, 24, came to see Such a Surge.
He's leaving a fan of Simon Says.
</P>
<P>
   ''These Americans are pretty good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the bus, the band's conversation ranges from girlfriends
to junk food to music. Always, there's an infusion of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did you know we're huge in Belgium?'' Franks asks.
</P>
<P>
   The guys howl with laughter. It's a running joke.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like that means anything,'' Franks explains. ''Who cares?
You're nothing anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   After the tour, the boys in the band are headed into a Los
Angeles studio to cut a second album before heading back to Germany
in August to play a two-day music festival, then on a U.S. tour.
</P>
<P>
   The band members say they're enjoying the musical ride, and
admit they've indulged in a few whims since they got a little
famous.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston bought a new Mustang. Diebels and Franks bought
motorcycles. Arrieta bought a top of the line laptop computer and a
Toyota Cellica.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly they look toward the future, putting their money into
savings and investments.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know it's not going to last forever,'' Johnston says. ''But
we're having a blast while we're doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.hollywoodrecords.go.com/simonsays
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Who's who in Simon Says:
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franks, 22, vocals, writes most of the band's lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The current album: ''The theme is deal with your problems and
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing: ''It can come to you anywhere -- driving down the road,
sitting in my bedroom. It's all stuff that we've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite song: ''Perfect Example. It's about everything I hate --
we all hate: phony people who say one thing ... and do another.''
</P>
<P>
   Life: ''The only things that really matter to me are Jen (Busby,
his fiance), my family and the guys in the band. The rest, well,
doesn't mean much without that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Zac Diebels, 23, guitar, writes the riffs and power chords, with
help from fellow band members, that are the band's trademark.
</P>
<P>
   Band's dynamic: ''We have strong feelings about music and life
in general. When we're asked, we'll give an honest answer, but
we're not going around spouting off as if it were our sacred
duty.''
</P>
<P>
   On success: ''We're not so self-serious that we need to force
ourselves down people's throats. We're lucky is what we are. Lucky
to have some talent and to have people want to hear our music.''
</P>
<P>
   His tattooed forearm: ''It says 'enjoy.' It's a reminder to me
to enjoy what I'm doing ... and not get caught up in the little
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Mike Johnston, 23, drums, asks the missing questions: ''Why are
we doing this?'' ''Is this the best decision for us?''
</P>
<P>
   Career: ''If we don't make it, I'm still going to be playing. I
can see being a studio (musician).''
</P>
<P>
   Touring: ''Of all of us, I'm the one who likes it the least. I'd
rather be in Sacramento, going to my favorite restaurants, doing
the things I like to do. ... But touring is part of the whole
thing, so I have to go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyle: ''None us smoke or do drugs. A couple of guys have a
beer. I don't drink at all. ... I'm not saying everybody has to be
a straight-edge, but that's me. I'd rather concentrate on my
health.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Mike Arrieta, 20, bass guitar, designs Web pages and answers the
band's e-mails on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Being the youngest: ''I'm allowed in to clubs to play, but after
we're done I have to leave. It's not like I'm drinking, but they
have rules. So the guys have to sneak me back in.''
</P>
<P>
   On performing: ''I get up there and I can just let it go. You're
supposed to be crazy when you perform. If you acted like that on
the street, you'd be a freak.''
</P>
<P>
   Life after Simon Says: ''Computers. Something computer- and
music-related. I enjoy both of them. I can't imagine them not being
a part of my life. But right now, I'm concentrating on the band.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
