<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capt. Cook, Darwin in Exhibition  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, England (AP) -- ''You will be amused with Fitz Roy's
Deluge Chapter -- Lyell ... has just read it &AMP; he says it beats all
the other nonsense he has ever read on the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The yellowing, tongue-in-cheek letter in the museum cabinet was
written by none other than Charles Darwin. He was describing
geologist Charles Lyell's reaction to an essay by meteorologist
Robert Fitzroy that argues for a literal reading of the biblical
account of Noah's flood.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1839 and Darwin, after five years surveying the wildlife
of the west coast of South America and some of the Pacific islands,
was convinced that the human species had evolved gradually over
millions of years.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzroy, a devout Christian who was captain of the Beagle, the
vessel that took Darwin on his voyage of discovery, had looked at
the same fossils and geological samples and concluded there was
proof that God created humankind -- and destroyed it by water.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of a new millennium, the evolution vs. creation
debate still resonates, and the letter has a prominent place in an
exhibit on time at Cambridge University Library. The library is
open only to accredited students and academics, but has recently
opened an exhibition section, with no admission fee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel it is important to make parts of our collection
available to the public,'' says Adam Perkins, archivist of the
Royal Greenwich Observatory library, the source of many of the
exhibits.
</P>
<P>
   Other exhibited items on evolutionary time include a map of
South America hand-colored and keyed by Darwin to show the
continent's geological makeup, with clay, granite and basaltic lava
all noted in the naturalist's spidery hand.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby is Darwin's hand-sketched and painted geological
cross-section of the Andes mountains, and also included is Darwin's
own copy of Lyell's ''Principles of Geology,'' which provided much
of the inspiration for Darwin's theories. Ironically, it was given
to him by Fitzroy.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the logbook from the Resolution, one of the ships
on the 1772-75 voyage of British naval explorer Capt. James Cook,
''bound on discoveries towards the South Pole.''
</P>
<P>
   The log was kept by astronomer William Wales, also a
cartographer who mapped the islands discovered by Cook, and
includes a carefully worked drawing of Norfolk Island in the
southern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Featured as well in the exhibition -- which runs through Sept. 15
-- is a lavishly illustrated, leather-bound Persian manuscript from
1566, a translation of the cosmography, or ''wonders of creation''
originally written in Arabic by the 13th-century geographer
Zakariya ibn Muhammad al-Qazwini.
</P>
<P>
   There is a deftly inscribed Chinese manuscript from 1478 showing
the workings of a clepsydra, or water clock, and a 1446 Sanskrit
time wheel written on palm leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition also looks at the development of time measurement
at Greenwich, including the plotting of longitude, and the 1967
discovery at Cambridge of pulsars, nicknamed ''ticking stars,''
neutron stars that spin hundreds of thousands of times per second.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a study of time in literature, from the poems of
Andrew Marvell to H.G. Wells' time machines.
</P>
<P>
   This section includes an early edition of Laurence Sterne's
''The life and opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman,'' in which
the 18th-century novelist offers a different theory of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea of duration,'' he writes, ''is got merely from the
train and succession of our ideas -- and is the true scholastick
pendulum.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.lib.cam.ac.uk/Exhibitions/Keeping--Time
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
