<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hollywood Classics: Milton Berle  </HEADLINE>
By BOB THOMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Milton Berle occupies a chair in
the bar section of the Friars Club dining room, not because he
wants a drink -- he says he is a lifelong teetotaler -- but because
the dining area is off-limits for cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the California sun shines brightly outside, Berle is
dressed for a wintry day: wool slacks, tweed sportcoat, pink shirt,
paisley tie, trenchcoat and a gray fedora cocked in rakish John
Barrymore style. He is 91, going on 92, and the years, nearly all
of them spent in show business, are catching up with him. A cane
rests at his side. He peers through thick glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a stroke a year ago,'' he explains, ''and the only thing
it affected was my eyes. I can't see very well.''
</P>
<P>
   His mind seems as sharp as ever. He can recount incidents of
70-80 years ago. He can reel off the latest jokes, a few bawdy,
most of them innocent. He can even tell Henny Youngman-style jokes
about his wife, Lorna, whom he adores: ''My wife has lots of money
-- mine ... I'm going to be 92 in July -- if my wife lets me.''
</P>
<P>
   On the wall behind Berle hang portraits of revered Friars:
Ronald Reagan, Bob Hope, Dean Martin, Jack Benny, George Burns, Al
Jolson. Of the old guard, only Berle remains active, and he
cherishes his status as Abbot Emeritus, the highest position in the
century-old club.
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, Friars members, singly and in pairs,
approach Berle, announcing their names because of his poor
eyesight. They seem like worshippers before a lama: ''I grew up
watching Uncle Miltie on television''; ''You're looking great,
Milton''; ''We love ya, Milton.'' All this from battle-hardened
veterans of show business.
</P>
<P>
   Berle lights a cigar, takes a few puffs, puts it in an ashtray
and allows it to go out. ''I never smoked a cigarette, but I've
smoked cigars since I was 12,'' he says. ''I figure if George Burns
can smoke 20 cigars a day all his life and live to be 100, why
should I worry if they're bad for me?''
</P>
<P>
   The saga of Milton Berle is inextricably bound to his mother,
Sandra, one of the classic stage mothers of show business. (Berle's
father, German immigrant Moses Berlinger, was a dreamer who lacked
the drive of his wife and son. He worked at various jobs, including
housepainter, paint salesman and night watchman.)
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother had always wanted to be in show business herself,''
Berle remarks. ''When she was young, it was sinful for a woman to
be an actress. The family forbade her. So she brought all her
energies into me.'' She had energy and nerve, having worked as a
detective in New York department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Little Milton's career began at 5, when he attracted attention
on the sidewalks of upper Manhattan with his Charlie Chaplin
imitations. An agent saw him and found him work as the Buster Brown
boy, the advertising image for a line of children's shoes. Chaplin
himself sent for the boy, and Milton appeared in silent films with
Chaplin, Marie Dressler, serial queen Pearl White, Mary Pickford
and Douglas Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
   Milton made his Broadway debut in a 1920 revival of the musical
''Floradora'' as a $15-a-week member of a boy sextet. Sandra Berle
then pushed her son into vaudeville, teaming him with a little girl
in a dramatic act as a juvenile Romeo and Juliet. They toured the
country and even played vaudeville's Valhalla, New York's Palace.
As he grew older, Milton shifted into a solo act, telling jokes,
singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mama was with me all the time,'' he recalls. ''She traveled
everywhere with me, made me do my homework on the road, and sat in
the audience for every show -- two a day, four a day, even when I
did 10 shows a day at the Steel Pier in Atlantic City. She used to
be a very big critic to me. She'd say, 'That joke didn't do very
well; take that joke out.'
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother held on to me with a tight grip; she didn't want to
lose me. It isn't considered right today, but I thought she had the
feeling of owning me and not wanting to be my mother but to be my
wife -- without incest. It's the old telltale story about the
mother's power over her son.
</P>
<P>
   ''She didn't worry about the girls I dated. But if I wanted to
get married -- not a chance. God love her, that was the silver cord
story between my mother and me. I didn't get married until I was
44. I hadn't had any real romances in my life until I met Joyce
Matthews, Miss America of 1940. My mother read in a column that I
was courting Joyce and she started to get shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   When Berle announced his plans to marry Joyce, his mother ''got
hysterical.'' But eventually she said, ''It's your life, get on
with it.'' She and Joyce became friends and often attended Milton's
performances together.
</P>
<P>
   Does Berle still dream about Sandra, who died in 1954?
</P>
<P>
   ''All the time, all the time. Reprimanding me, loving me,
cuddling me, bawling me out, different moods.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1940s, Berle remained a headliner in radio, movies
and Broadway shows, and at nightclubs in Las Vegas, New York and
Miami. Then in 1948, his career took a different turn.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Texaco people came to me and said they wanted me to do a
television show,'' he recounted. ''I felt like trying a new medium,
and I thought I knew as much about television as anybody else. They
asked me what my format would be. I said I would do what I had been
trained to do and what I did best: vaudeville.''
</P>
<P>
   Able to earn top dollar in Las Vegas -- $25,000 a week -- Berle
started on the Tuesday night ''Texaco Star Theater'' for $1,500 per
show.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Sales of TV sets boomed, and movie house operators
lamented: ''On Tuesday nights you could shoot a cannon through the
theater and not hit a soul.''
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times writer commented: ''Television didn't make
Milton Berle; Milton Berle made television.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to host, direct, choreograph and script 182 live
hours for Texaco, and later some 60 hours for the replacement
''Buick-Berle Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of stars made their TV debuts on ''Texaco Star Theater,''
and Berle calmed their concerns about the new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were all scared, especially when they came from Hollywood
to New York,'' said Berle. ''I told them, 'Don't worry about the
camera or hitting your marks. Just be relaxed and do your act, and
I'll have the cameras follow you.' When I wasn't on, I was
backstage with a headset, telling the booth: 'Put a wide angle on
this shot. ... Move in for a close-up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Berle was on. He wore outrageous costumes, often in
drag. He sang, he hoofed, he told jokes and milked them if they
bombed. He injected himself into the other acts. It was 60 minutes
of startling entertainment, the likes of which most Americans had
never seen before. Highbrows adored the sophisticated comedy of Sid
Caesar and Imogene Coca. The masses fell in love with Uncle Miltie.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month, Berle sued NBC for more than $30 million,
claiming the network lost or gave away 133 episodes of the landmark
show, which he had hoped to sell to the public. NBC did not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   When Milton Berle finally exhausted his TV shtick and audience
in 1955, he continued as a top attraction in Vegas and elsewhere;
appeared in movies and TV series, often in dramatic roles; wrote
memoirs; performed public service, and served as adviser for
seniors for the President's Council on Physical Fitness.
</P>
<P>
   The stroke a few months after his 90th birthday ended his days
as a performer. He professes not to miss it: ''I believe I have
paid my dues. Instead of making people laugh, I want to make myself
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he has entered a new career: professor emeritus of comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Every two months, he holds a seminar at the Friars Club.
Aspiring comics, none of them old enough to have known Berle as Mr.
Television, have lunch and ask him questions.
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ''I tell my classes, 'Everything has to have a
beginning, a middle and an end, whether it's a play, a movie, a
book, or even a one-liner. If you've got an opening and an end but
no middle, you're in trouble. If you've got a middle and an end but
no opening, you're in trouble. If you have everything put together,
you can kill the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you're Uncle Miltie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 1204 </TRAILER>
