<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Song Becomes Anthem for Occasions  </HEADLINE>
By MARTA W. ALDRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- In a misty-eyed rite of passage at HUM
School for Little People, graduation ceremonies open each spring
with a procession of wide-eyed preschoolers marching in to the
recorded strains of ''Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian singer Michael W. Smith's song has become an anthem
for special occasions -- graduations, weddings, even funerals --
although it's 18 years old and rarely played on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was asked to sing it last year at memorial services for
the students slain at Columbine High School and for professional
golfer Payne Stewart, who was killed in a plane crash. In 1992,
Smith performed it at the White House as a farewell tribute to
George and Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
   How does one ballad bridge so many gaps?
</P>
<P>
   ''It speaks to something we try to emphasize in our school,''
said Billie Aita, a teacher at HUM. ''And that's friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the song has an appeal beyond its initial
contemporary Christian music audience because ''it's a simple song
that works.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It stirs people's emotions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has won 25 Gospel Music Association Dove Awards, says
he couldn't complete a concert without performing ''Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My audience wouldn't receive me very well if I left it out.
They're always waiting for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The song's reach and staying power led contemporary Christian
music critics in 1998 to vote ''Friends'' the genre's all-time No.
1 song.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing company owning the rights to ''Friends'' annually
gets requests for permission to reprint the lyrics in senior
yearbooks, on greeting cards and coffee mugs and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ''This song tends to recycle itself every few years,'' said
Casey McGinty, vice president of EMI Christian Music Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   ''A new group will come up in high school or college that seems
to identify with it, and it makes its way into the hearts of a
whole new generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The song's lingering popularity surprises no one more than
Smith, who co-wrote ''Friends'' with his wife, Debbie, in spring
1982, just before he began touring as Amy Grant's opening act.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths wrote it to mark the departure of a good friend who
had taught an informal weekly Bible study in their Nashville duplex
during their newlywed year.
</P>
<P>
   ''My wife thought we should do something special for him and I
thought, 'Great idea, we'll get him a gift.' But she thought we
should write him a song and play it for him that very night. I
said, 'You're out of your mind. We can't write songs that fast.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, she had written the lyrics and, five
minutes later, he had penned the music.
</P>
<P>
   Smith sang it that night for their study group, where
''everybody cried.'' The song anchored his first album the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Though Smith has since had 23 No. 1 songs on Christian radio and
seven top 25 tunes on mainstream radio, it is ''Friends'' that
generates the most mail -- most of which Smith says ''will just move
you to tears.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent note from a couple in LaMoille, Ill., describes the
1998 automobile deaths of their teen-age son and his friend, both
of whom would have graduated from high school this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Friends'' was played at each funeral and will be sung at this
year's commencement, where the boys' parents will give each
graduate a ''Friends'' CD.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent concert in Edmonton, Alberta, Smith said, 14,000
young people sang along with him, word for word.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can look down and there's always two, three, four kids
holding onto each other and weeping. I can't even look at them
because I start crying, too. I don't know their exact story, but I
can tell they have lost a classmate or friend or loved one.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Smith said she is honored the song is often used ''for
life's big moments,'' especially in an age when few popular songs
explore friendship beyond romance or partying.
</P>
<P>
   ''The songs are already there for the romantic side of
friendship,'' she said. ''I much prefer to encourage friendship
that carries you through the hard times.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Lyrics to the song ''Friends,'' written by Michael W. Smith and
Deborah D. Smith:
</P>
<P>
   Packing up the dreams God planted
</P>
<P>
   In the fertile soil of you
</P>
<P>
   Can't believe the hopes He's granted
</P>
<P>
   Means a chapter in your life is through
</P>
<P>
   But we'll keep you close as always
</P>
<P>
   It won't even seem you've gone
</P>
<P>
   'Cause our hearts in big and small ways
</P>
<P>
   Will keep the love that keeps us strong.
</P>
<P>
   Chorus:
</P>
<P>
   And friends are friends forever
</P>
<P>
   If the Lord is the Lord of them
</P>
<P>
   And a friend will not say ''Never''
</P>
<P>
   'Cause the welcome will not end
</P>
<P>
   Though it's hard to let you go.
</P>
<P>
   In the Father's hands we know
</P>
<P>
   That a lifetime's not too long to live as friends.
</P>
<P>
   With the faith and love God's given
</P>
<P>
   Springing from the hope we know
</P>
<P>
   We will pray the joy you'll live in
</P>
<P>
   Is the strength that now you show
</P>
<P>
   But we'll keep you close as always
</P>
<P>
   It won't even seem you've gone
</P>
<P>
   'Cause our hearts in big and small ways
</P>
<P>
   Will keep the love that keeps us strong.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat chorus
</P>
