<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Uncertainty of Friendship  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It's the most intellectually challenging play on
Broadway in years. An unlikely hit about two real-life physicists
that is more about the nature of friendship than the meaning of
fission and fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the popularity of ''Copenhagen,'' the favorite to win the
best-play Tony Award June 4, remains as much a puzzle to its author
as the drama's dense discussion of quantum physics does to most
people in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Just why has ''Copenhagen'' captured the attention of
theatergoers more used to singing cats, falling chandeliers and
stage retreads of Hollywood disco movies from the 1970s?
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea,'' says English playwright Michael Frayn with
an almost gleeful laugh. He's not being difficult. The genial,
white-haired author of such works as ''Noises Off,''
''Benefactors'' and ''Wild Honey'' is unfailingly polite. Frayn
just doesn't know for sure. And not knowing for sure -- a lack of
certainty -- is what ''Copenhagen'' is all about.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart, ''Copenhagen'' is a mystery, according to Frayn,
which may explain part of its success. Why did German physicist
Werner Heisenberg travel to Denmark in 1941 to meet with his
colleague and old mentor, Niels Bohr, the great Danish scientist?
The men were now on opposite sides in a great war, and the Germans
were taking their first tentative steps toward developing the atom
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation between Bohr and Heisenberg was never revealed.
The play is speculation on the event by Frayn, who studied
philosophy not physics in school. Yet it wasn't the scientific
discussions between the two men that attracted Frayn to their
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It focused on something that has always interested me
philosophically, which is how we know why people do what they do,''
says the 66-year-old Frayn, a former journalist who worked for The
Guardian and as a columnist for The Observer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it seems very obvious. You feel hungry. So you eat.
But a lot of human actions are more complicated than that. It's
very, very difficult to ascribe motives to them. But we have to
try.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to look at the external evidence, look at the
people's behavior -- what they say, the way they deport themselves --
and make some kind of estimate. But that's different from having
precise, firsthand knowledge of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The playwright believes there is a theoretical barrier to ever
understanding people's motives directly. He sees a parallel with
Heisenberg's uncertainty principle in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ''His principle implies that you can never have absolutely
definite knowledge of the physical world for everyday purposes,''
Frayn explains.
</P>
<P>
   That ambiguity intrigued him, spurring him to begin work on the
play. Frayn struggled with its form for a long time, finding it
difficult to organize all the scientific and historical material.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried writing it all kinds of different ways,'' he says. In
the end, he decided to portray its three characters -- Heisenberg,
Bohr and Bohr's wife, Margrethe -- after they had died, looking back
on their lives.
</P>
<P>
   After all, according to Frayn, that's what the story seemed to
be -- about these three people trying to locate what had happened in
Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no agreement about that for a start -- what Heisenberg
actually said,'' Frayn says. ''And secondly, what his intentions
were.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his intentions about atomic weapons in general, Frayn
continues: ''Was he actually trying to build them? Or was he really
trying not to build them? Or was he somewhere in the middle?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Copenhagen,'' which was directed by Frayn's longtime
collaborator Michael Blakemore, premiered at the Royal National
Theater in London in May 1998 and later moved to the West End,
where it is still running. The Broadway version, starring Philip
Bosco as Bohr, Michael Cumpsty as Heisenberg and Blair Brown as
Bohr's wife, opened in April.
</P>
<P>
   ''Copenhagen'' is the sixth collaboration between Frayn and
Blakemore.
</P>
<P>
   ''I show him what I think is a finished draft, but it never is a
finished draft because we then go through it together and he always
makes suggestions about changing it. Not so much with this play,
but with 'Noises Off' he persuaded me to do an enormous amount of
rewriting.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Michael and I literally go through it line by line, word by
word. It's a very slow and laborious process, but he makes me
explain what is happening and then offers suggestions. It's a way
of examining the text very closely.''
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Frayn thought of calling the play ''The Copenhagen
Interpretation,'' but finally thought ''Copenhagen'' simply was
more appropriate. Others disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Queen of Denmark, who is an extremely intelligent and
educated woman, came to see the play in London and when the play
was done in Copenhagen, she told the producers, 'You've got to
change the title, because you can't have a play called
''Copenhagen'' in Copenhagen.'
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was very striking that a member of the Danish
royal family would take that level of intelligent interest in the
play. The second most striking thing was the producers didn't pay
any attention to her at all.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the world of science also have been interested -- and
complimentary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scientists have been very generous about the play,'' Frayn
says. ''I expected them to be irritated by some stupid layman
trampling all over their subject. Some of them have pointed out
mistakes, but I hope I've got them all out now. Still, I think I
will have a few more people in New York saying something by the
time the play ends its run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 1204 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
