<DOCNO> APW20000524.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fun Is the difference for Steely Dan  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For Walter Becker and Donald Fagen, the two men
behind Steely Dan, there's a simple difference between touring now
and touring 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they're enjoying themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, Fagen and their 12-piece band are spending most of the
summer in concert amphitheatres across the country, performing hits
such as ''Peg,'' ''Rikki Don't Lose That Number'' and ''Deacon
Blues,'' plus songs from their first album in 19 years, ''Two
Against Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was, like, tortured when we were on the road in the '70s,''
Fagen says. ''I was a mess. This is the most fun we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Steely Dan exists now primarily as a touring outfit.
Their concerts provided the impetus for the new album; Becker and
Fagen were starting to perform new songs and realized it's easier
for audiences if they have a chance to get to know the music
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   That's an intriguing turn of events for anyone who knows Steely
Dan's history.
</P>
<P>
   Becker and Fagen, who met as students at Bard College, formed
the band hurriedly in 1972 after making their first album under the
name Steely Dan, and performed frequently.
</P>
<P>
   But they quit abruptly in 1975, disbanded the group, and instead
concentrated on writing and recording as a twosome. They produced
their best-known work over the next five years, and developed a
reputation as studio hermits and perfectionists. In their prime, no
one got to hear Steely Dan's music in concert.
</P>
<P>
   They have unpleasant memories of their early days on the road.
Steely Dan was mostly an opening act, struggling with lousy sound
systems, an inconsistent band and staying in cheap motels. They
were piling up debt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, we were traveling around in close company with
people who were really having a good time and partying and we
weren't,'' Becker says. ''It was also a total drain from the
creative process of writing songs and making records, which we
needed to keep going at a certain pace just to have enough money to
live. Now, all of these things are more or less reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Touring today means comfortable hotel rooms, star billing and
competent, consistent musicians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, we're traveling with likable, professional players,''
Becker says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody is drunk,'' Fagen interjects.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody is freaking out,'' Becker continues. ''The police
aren't coming in looking for anybody. Nobody is banging holes in
the walls of hotel rooms. WE'RE not banging holes in the walls of
hotel rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they were never the type to toss TVs in the swimming
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don and I just weren't the guys who wanted to get into a rock
'n' roll band for that particular reason,'' Becker says. ''We ...
wanted to write songs and put echo on stuff and mix records.''
</P>
<P>
   The music business has changed with them. For most acts that
appeal primarily to an older audience, concert tours are where the
money is made now. Fans of artists such as Steely Dan are generally
more interested in hearing classic songs than seeking out CDs of
new material, even though the sales performance of ''Two Against
Nature'' puts a dent in that theory.
</P>
<P>
   The album debuted at No. 6 in Billboard and has sold more than
600,000 copies. That's not bad considering the wait since their
last disc -- or record, since compact discs weren't even around
then.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was delighted,'' Becker says. ''It could have been
completely dismissed as a couple of old guys getting together to
try and bang out a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagen, sitting with his friend in a New York office, has a
different way of measuring it. ''I noticed this girl who just came
in to give us some water, she gave us a really big smile,'' he
says. ''Six weeks ago, we were just shmendriks. She couldn't care
less.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not true,'' Becker chides him. ''She's just like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men have the easygoing rapport of old friends who can
finish each other's sentences and don't need the punchline to
chuckle at old jokes. They argue good-naturedly about differences
in music over the past two decades. Fagen thinks it hasn't changed
much; Becker isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   There's no dramatic tale to tell of their breakup in the early
1980s. They had grown apart socially and needed time to do some
work on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think, like a lot of Americans, we were still in our
adolescence at age 30 or so, and we kind of ran out of steam as far
as life material,'' Fagen says.
</P>
<P>
   Critics found ''Two Against Nature'' remarkable for the way it
seemed to make time stand still; the break could just as easily
have been 19 weeks instead of 19 years. Their music has a slightly
snappier, rhythm 'n' blues feel to it, but it's basically the
airtight jazz-pop that is their signature.
</P>
<P>
   Becker and Fagen find that talk amusing, figuring it's based on
an assumption they're going to change what they do best. Was anyone
expecting a rap album?
</P>
<P>
   Their music is actually a favorite of many rappers, who are
often asking for permission to sample Steely Dan on their own
discs. Becker and Fagen usually grant it, figuring it's just the
modern equivalent of a long musical tradition of borrowing a chord
progression or lyric.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say it isn't a little strange to be sharing space
on the charts with artists who weren't born during Steely Dan's
first go-round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 1205 </TRAILER>
