<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conan O'Brien's Sidekick To Leave  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Maybe, just maybe, this is all some elaborate
joke. Andy Richter has always been able to keep a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. Richter, Conan O'Brien's partner on NBC's ''Late
Night'' for seven years, really meant it when he said he was going
to leave his seat on the couch. Andy's exit comes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The duo will sift through an hour's worth of clips -- Richter
calls it ''a eulogy in which the corpse is present'' -- and then
O'Brien will be on his own.
</P>
<P>
   It's a measure of how far ''Late Night'' has come in seven years
that Richter, who some NBC executives wanted off the air much more
quickly in the show's early days, is permitted a bittersweet,
extended coda.
</P>
<P>
   No animosity surrounds the exit. Richter told O'Brien more than
a year ago that he wanted to try something different, and admitted
he's been a little bored.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love this show, I'm proud of this show, and I'm proud of my
involvement,'' Richter said. ''I didn't want to start becoming
bitter about it. I thought if I stick around here I'm going to
start becoming an unpleasant person, and this place doesn't deserve
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter has always considered himself a comedic actor and
writer, and talk-show sidekick never figured into his career plan.
</P>
<P>
   Those talents enabled him to transcend the role. A skit that
appeared a few weeks ago was typical: He began by chatting with
O'Brien about potential replacements and then introduced his
''little sister'' in the audience. She had a crush on Conan and
desperately wanted the job.
</P>
<P>
   The retainer-wearing actress was a plant, of course. The comedic
bit escalated into slapstick, climaxing with ''little sister''
smashing a bottle over Richter's head.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no word, really, for what it was that Andy brought to
the show,'' O'Brien said. ''We never said, 'You be the Ed McMahon
sidekick, in the traditional role.' The idea was, 'Let's have this
funny guy who has a different rhythm than me sit next to me and do
whatever he wants.'''
</P>
<P>
   If the idea wasn't to have the second coming of Ed McMahon,
O'Brien at least wanted viewers to believe Richter could be.
O'Brien envisions ''Late Night'' as looking like Johnny Carson's
''Tonight'' show circa 1965, with a subversive layer of comedy
lurking beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Richter fit the part perfectly, with his dry humor and baby
face, which makes him, at 33, still look like he's pledging John
Belushi's fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of Andy Richter fans think he's this frat guy, but they
don't know he has very sophisticated tastes,'' O'Brien said. ''He
doesn't want to chug a beer. He wants a vodka and tonic, and he
wears a nice smoking jacket at a party.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter was hired as a writer, but he and O'Brien bonded in the
months before the show debuted and it was decided he would be in
front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   At first, ratings and critical notices were tough.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were so battered in the beginning, battered and fried, that
even when the compliments started, they were sort of left-handed
compliments,'' Richter said. ''The classic left-handed compliment
was, 'You're getting so much better.' That always implied that we
really sucked.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien recalls some of his favorite Richter moments, including
when Andy dressed up as Alanis Morissette. Richter had some of his
best times going out on location, like at Woodstock, where ''Late
Night'' cameras could have fun with bystanders without making fun
of them.
</P>
<P>
   He wishes he had more time to do other things, but the
five-day-a-week ''Late Night'' has demanded monagamy.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I really want most for Andy Richter is for him to be
happy, and I want him to do what makes him happy,'' O'Brien said.
''If staying here for five more years would make him feel like he's
not taking a chance that he needs to take and he starts being
unhappy because of that, it wouldn't be the same Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter won't be replaced right away. O'Brien will fly solo, and
maybe later in the summer test some guests in the role.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be like a widow who wears black for awhile and
doesn't go dating, and then slowly I'll be seen around town with a
gentleman caller,'' O'Brien said. ''And then maybe I'm happily
married in a year or so. If so, great.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter is slowly working himself into other roles. He was the
voice of a talking dog in a pilot television series that, so far,
NBC hasn't picked up. He plays one of Richard Gere's buddies in the
upcoming film ''Dr. T and the Women.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My wife and I are going to the Caribbean for 10 days after I
leave,'' he said, ''and that's about as far forward as I'm looking.
Most of what I'm feeling is, 'I can't wait to get to that beach.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE JOB: Singer Don Henley is giving viewers an inside look
at his ''Inside Job.'' To promote his new album, he'll perform
Thursday live from Dallas for the A&AMP;E Network's ''Live By Request''
show. He'll take song requests via telephone and the Internet
during the performance. The program airs at 9 p.m. EDT, and will be
repeated on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   David Bauder can be reached at dbauder''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
