<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chumbawamba Likes Hits, Anarchy  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The eight members of the English rock group
Chumbawamba see no reason why anarchists can't enjoy a hit record.
</P>
<P>
   ''WYSIWYG'' (''What You See Is What You Get'') was just released
by Universal Records. The album is a follow-up to 1997's
''Tubthumper,'' which contained the hit single ''Tubthumping,'' an
ode to drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Chumbawamba, whose members include guitarist Boff, trumpeter
Jude Abbott and vocalist Dunstan Bruce, didn't want to clone its
previous album.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our previous record was 12 songs. This is 22, which play
together -- like sound bites and collages in art -- as one whole
piece,'' Ms. Abbott said. ''It's a snapshot of what is going on in
the world. The previous record was centered on the north of
England.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject matter on ''WYSIWYG'' includes dumbing down, rich
girls becoming social commentators and the growing influence of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the music is sweeter on this one and the lyrics more
vitriolic,'' Boff said. ''On the last album, the bass and drums
were programmed. On this one, a lot of those things were live.
There was more room for us to experiment with the way we sounded.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't against Chumbawamba's anarchist principles to have a
hit single. In fact, band members enjoy the platform
''Tubthumping'' has given them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought we'd written songs before that were good singles,''
Boff said. ''For one reason or another, they never sold. Our hit
was more by accident than by design. If we knew how, we would have
had a hit years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been obsessed with the idea of popular culture and being
part of that, rather than spending years and years outside of
things. You get bands who are happy to stay in their own scene or
don't like the idea of having a record that's popular. It wasn't a
problem for us at all.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ''Tubthumping'' did take them on a roller coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a hit all around the world and we were in demand
everywhere at once,'' Boff said. ''It was a totally new experience
for us. We'd been used for years to putting out records, touring
Europe for a month, touring England for a month and taking a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people think of Chumbawamba as a party band.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what was so good about the success,'' Ms. Abbott said.
''Every time we were interviewed, it became obvious we had another
agenda. It was a brilliant opportunity, which is why it was worth
18 months of complete mayhem.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the band never has another hit, it won't go back to its
previous underground status, Bruce said. ''Before the hit, we'd
never sold any records in Japan. If we never have a hit again, we
can still go to Japan and play there.''
</P>
<P>
   Chumbawamba defines anarchism as a fight to keep society from
being corrupted by institutions of authority.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nothing to do with chaos and disorganization,'' Bruce
said. ''It is actually about social organization, really structured
and well-organized, between people. There would be no government,
no bosses and no majority rule. Everybody's education is based
around this notion there has to be leaders. It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The band, while believing governments should be thrown out, is
more interested in what is happening around the world. At present,
the group's attention is focused on attacks on Asians and blacks in
England and other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   When Chumbawamba began 18 years ago, the band lived together in
an abandoned house -- with the owner's permission. ''It was
fantastic. None of us had any money and the collective idea was how
we wanted to live and what we wanted to do,'' Bruce said.
</P>
<P>
   Chumbawamba had its own record company and sold records at
concerts and by mail order. ''Pictures of Starving Children Sell
Records'' was the title of the band's first album.
</P>
<P>
   Band members describe their songwriting method as getting
together and discussing a direction for an upcoming album, then
each going off and writing fragments of lyrics or music.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a bit like a jigsaw (puzzle),'' Ms. Abbott said. ''We fit
in bits and pieces until the whole thing emerges.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does Chumbawamba mean?
</P>
<P>
   ''We've amused ourselves by giving alternative reasons for where
it came from,'' Boff said. ''The word doesn't mean anything at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The official Web site for Chumbawamba is: http://www.chumba.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 1314 </TRAILER>
