<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Across country from parched Southwest, rain spells big losses for onion farmers </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELBA, N.Y. (AP) -- They call it the Big O Farm -- O for onions
grown by Ognibene &AMP; Sons for 60 years. With all the rain of late,
enough to temporarily turn some of Elba's mucklands into foot-deep
lakes, this year's harvest could end up close to a Big Zero.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are they going to make it? I don't know, they look pretty
sick,'' said Steve Ognibene, 44, stoically surveying long rows of
green onion tips barely peeping through the waterlogged black soil.
''They should be three inches high by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the continent from the tinderbox Southwest, where
wildfires have devastated Los Alamos, N.M., some spots in the
Northeast are getting twice as much spring rain as usual. Farmers
in soggy western New York have endured weeks of frustration, and a
few could be out of business before it dries up.
</P>
<P>
   Onions are among the costliest commodities to sow at around
$2,000 an acre. At the end of March, Ognibene began planting the
800-acre farm he's worked since age 14, and finished up early this
month just in time for the heavens to open.
</P>
<P>
   The worst came on a mid-May weekend when a fleet of
thunderstorms dumped 3 inches of rain. Drainage ditches that
crisscross the 3,000-acre mucklands near Lake Ontario overflowed.
Some onion and potato fields were submerged for longer than 24
hours -- a perilous duration.
</P>
<P>
   ''With too much water, you can't get enough oxygen to the root
system and the plant suffocates,'' Ognibene explained, dark streaks
under his eyes accentuated by 14-hour workdays.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 75 percent of the onion crop could be lost in the
lowlands, which were converted from swamp in the 1930s. Only about
a dozen large farms operate here now, compared with scores of
5-acre to 15-acre plots when Ognibene's grandfather emigrated from
Sicily during the Depression, and their number could soon contract
even more.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Riner thinks he'll lose at least one-third of his 240-acre
onion crop but hopes to soak up his losses in upland fields set
aside for cabbage, peas, green beans, field corn, wheat and
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
   As in other parts of upstate New York and into Vermont, however,
those plantings have been delayed nearly three weeks already by
excessive rain -- and there's no sign of a break in the clouds.
About 9 inches have fallen here since April, nearly 5 inches above
normal.
</P>
<P>
   Some smaller-scale farmers who rely solely on onions and
potatoes could have difficulty surviving.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try not to think of that,'' said Nancy Rowcliffe, whose
husband's onion fields were waterlogged. ''I really don't know how
much chance there is of recovering any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarked Riner, ''Out West, where it doesn't rain a lot and they
use supplemental irrigation water, maybe the risk in agriculture
isn't quite as high. But certainly here, Mother Nature plays a huge
role in the success or failure of a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he calls himself an eternal optimist. ''Even when
the weatherman says it's going to rain tomorrow, you hope there's a
chance it's going to go around you,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Ognibene, his next-door neighbor, knows only too well the need
to keep farming setbacks in perspective -- in 1993, his wife was
killed and two of their four children were fatally injured in a car
crash. And although he still runs the Big O Farm, the burden has
eased somewhat since his father, Joe, sold the farm last year to
another local family.
</P>
<P>
   What hasn't changed is the struggle it takes to get the product
grown.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have labor, weather, insect, fungus problems,'' Ognibene
said. ''When you think you got one solved, you get another one. And
then it's too dry or too wet and the wind's blowing too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''I laugh too. That's the only way you can get through
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
