<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gene Lab: No More Research on Humans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The University of Pennsylvania's gene
therapy institute, under fire over the death of an Arizona
teen-ager during an experiment last September, will no longer
perform research on humans, the school said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute for Human Gene Therapy will instead focus on
animal experiments and other basic research into gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration already had halted all clinical
trials at the institute, citing serious violations of federal
research rules important for patient safety.
</P>
<P>
   The institute came under investigation last fall when
18-year-old Jesse Gelsinger died four days after receiving
experimental therapy there. He was the first person known to have
died as a result of gene therapy.
</P>
<P>
   University spokeswoman Lori Doyle said Penn will continue to
conduct clinical trials in gene therapy, but that they will not be
done by the institute.
</P>
<P>
   And the institute's director, Dr. James M. Wilson, may be
consulted in the design of these gene therapy experiments, ''but he
will not sponsor clinical trials. He will not participate,'' Penn
President Judith Rodin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodin said the university will also strengthen oversight of gene
therapy research and other clinical trials, and review its
conflict-of-interest policies.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, one of genetics' brightest stars, founded a company in
1992 that had exclusive rights to discoveries made at his
institute. That financial relationship raised additional concern
about the experiment that killed Gelsinger.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said in a statement that he will remain as the gene
institute's director, hoping to develop ''a foundation of science
necessary to ensure the ultimate success of this field. Although
numerous scientific obstacles exist, gene therapy has tremendous
potential to someday prevent or cure life-threatening diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
offered a proposal to strengthen the safety of medical experiments
by fining scientists who violate federal research rules up to
$250,000, and universities up to $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
