<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fox Names Entertainment Chief  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fox has hired studio chief Gail Berman, the
executive producer of ''Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' to be the
network's new entertainment president.
</P>
<P>
   Berman has been president of Regency Television, a production
house aligned with Fox Television Studios that makes ''Malcolm in
the Middle'' for Fox and ''Roswell'' for the WB network.
</P>
<P>
   She replaces Doug Herzog, who quit after 14 months when a new
executive, Sandy Grushow, was hired to run both the network and
Fox's television studio.
</P>
<P>
   Berman's hiring was widely expected ever since Herzog left two
months ago. She said she wanted to stay at Regency to see whether
any of the programs that the studio was developing would land on
network schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Two Regency properties made it onto fall schedules when they
were announced last week: ''Fearsum'' on Fox and ''Tucker'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the fourth-ranked broadcast network, suffered through a
disastrous year in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from its special, ''Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire,'' caused Grushow to renounce reality programming.
The success of two new comedies, ''Malcolm in the Middle'' and
''Titus,'' was a bright spot.
</P>
<P>
   With eight new series planned for the fall, Fox is making more
extensive schedule changes than any other network.
</P>
<P>
   Berman said she's not concerned with Fox's track record in
chewing through entertainment chiefs: Herzog was the fifth person
to hold the job in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to create an atmosphere where creativity will blossom
and people will feel secure that I will be around,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
