<HEADLINE> Tech Stocks Lead Nasdaq Selloff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks remained in a slump today,
driving the Nasdaq composite index to its sixth consecutive loss.
Trading was once again volatile, with the weakness in technology
threatening to dismantle the broad market's modest gains.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index
was down 60.99 at 3,103.56.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators had recovered from midday declines and
were mostly higher. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 42.15
at 10,464.42, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 1.41 at
1,375.27.
</P>
<P>
   Technology shares dragged the Nasdaq lower, continuing a slide
that has knocked the Nasdaq 39 percent below its March 10 peak of
5,048.62. The technology sector has borne the brunt of investors'
worries over rising rates, which are expected to cut into corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, investors attacked the largest, best-capitalized
companies, which just weeks ago were seen as a safe haven. JDS
Uniphase fell 3 63/64 to 75 9/64 and Qualcomm fell 7 47/64 to 71
41/64.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors have determined that technology stocks, still
among the most expensive issues on the market, are too highly
priced given the weakening outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a bear market in technology,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp. ''What worries me is that
it's beginning to look like more than just a valuation problem.
Investors are now wondering if earnings estimates for tech
companies are too high at a time when interest rates are going
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, one of the biggest decliners in the technology-dominated
Nasdaq was Costco Wholesale Corp., a representative of the ''old
economy.'' Shares fell 10{ to 30[ after the company said it missed
earnings estimates in the fiscal third quarter and is also likely
to miss fourth-quarter estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks drew the most buying interest after UAL, the
parent company of United Airlines, said it is buying US Airways for
$4.3 billion in cash. In addition to the cash payment, UAL will
assume $7.3 billion in debt and aircraft operating leases. That
heavy debt load pared UAL shares by 9[ to 51\.
</P>
<P>
   But US Airways shares soared 22] to 48 5/16. Meanwhile, news of
the merger enlivened the rest of the airline sector. For the most
part, shares of regional airlines that are also seen as takeover
targets rose. Alaska Air rose 2~ to 31 7/16 and KLM Airlines rose 2
11/16 to 23 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   Larger airlines that are perceived as potential buyers slipped.
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, fell 3~ to 28}.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 744.50 million
shares, well ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 12.05 to 446.96.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
