<HEADLINE> Young named as head of Newington skating center  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWINGTON, Conn. (AP) -- Figure skating coach Bob Young, who
brought Olympic gold medalists to Simsbury, is hoping to do the
same here in his new job as executive director of the Connecticut
Skating Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very exciting,'' said Young. ''We'd like to continue to
do the same thing here and we'd like to put Newington on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Young, 45, resigned earlier this month as coach of the
International Skating Center of Connecticut in Simsbury amid
allegations of sexual harassment by a former student.
</P>
<P>
   He declined Wednesday to comment on the case, saying ''I'm
focusing on the future.'' As far as the status the case, he said,
''I don't have that information right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he resigned from the Simsbury center to ''move
forward to a new opportunity,'' not to escape the allegations by
23-year-old skater Jessica Roos.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Roos, who trained at the Simsbury facility, filed a
lawsuit claiming Young made sexually oriented comments and
inappropriately touched her for nearly five years. Young has
maintained his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Roos has said she sees Young's departure as a vindication of her
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who was responsible for bringing Olympic gold medalists
Oksana Baiul, Ekaterina Gordeeva and Viktor Petrenko to train in
Connecticut, was placed on paid leave in February. He had worked in
Simsbury for nearly six years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The East Granby resident, who grew up in East Hartford, said he
is looking forward to returning to his ''old back yard.'' Young
would not get specific, but said he has been working diligently on
plans that would be announced soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking world wide right now,'' he said. ''The Olympics is
upcoming in two years-- and in the U.S.-- the same situation as in
1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Budnick, the center owner, said he plans to make a
''major announcement'' within the next two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who began skating at age 13, was 15 when it ''just
clicked.'' He joined the U.S. National Figure Skating Team as an
amateur in 1967 and turned professional in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's absolutely the most experienced person who is capable of
organizing a top-notch figure skating program,'' said Budnick. ''He
brings us a level of professionalism that's second-to-none.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, which opened in February 1999, already is
established in ice hockey. The general manager, Chris Kiene, is a
former defenseman for the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope to do the same with skating that he's done with
hockey,'' said Young.
</P>
<P>
   Roos' lawsuit was to be heard by the state's Commission on Human
Rights and Opportunities. A message was left Wednesday at the CHRO
office.
</P>
<P>
   Simsbury police were also investigating Roos' allegations. A
message was left for detectives Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
