<HEADLINE> Dow Up 108; Nasdaq Up 48  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned higher today as blue-chip
technology stocks made a modest recovery, lifting the Nasdaq
composite index out of its sixth consecutive loss. Trading was once
again volatile, with market averages changing course several times.
</P>
<P>
   With less than an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular
session, the Nasdaq composite was up 47.95 at 3,212.50. Earlier in
the day, the Nasdaq had been down as much as 121 points.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators had also recovered from midday declines
and were nearing their high points of the day. The Dow Jones
industrial average was up 107.60 at 10,529.87, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 18.90 at 1,392.76.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks reversed their declines as investors began seeking
bargains in the battered technology sector. Steep, steady selling
in the past few sessions has wiped away nearly all of the
spectacular gains the Nasdaq achieved between early November and
early March.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the largest, best-capitalized companies, which some
see as a safe haven, erased early declines. Cisco Systems rose 4
1/64 to 54 9/16 and Intel rose 7[ to 117. Applied Materials rose 4
13/16 to 76 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have borne the brunt of investors' worries
over rising rates, which are expected to cut into corporate
profits. Many investors have determined that technology stocks,
still among the most expensive issues on the market, are too highly
priced given the weakening outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a bear market in technology,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief
investment officer at First Albany Corp. ''What worries me is that
it's beginning to look like more than just a valuation problem.
Investors are now wondering if earnings estimates for tech
companies are too high at a time when interest rates are going
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors proved willing to reward technology companies
that are performing well. Intuit rose 5 15/16 to 33 after releasing
an upbeat profit report.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks drew the most buying interest after UAL, the
parent company of United Airlines, said it is buying US Airways for
$4.3 billion in cash. In addition to the cash payment, UAL will
assume $7.3 billion in debt and aircraft operating leases. That
heavy debt load pared UAL shares by 7~ to 52{.
</P>
<P>
   But US Airways shares soared 22] to 48 5/16. Meanwhile, news of
the merger enlivened the rest of the airline sector. For the most
part, shares of regional airlines that are also seen as takeover
targets rose. Alaska Air rose 2~ to 31 7/16 and KLM Airlines rose
2} to 23\.
</P>
<P>
   Larger airlines that are perceived as potential buyers slipped.
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, fell 3~ to 28}.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 906.99 million
shares, well ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 4.47 to 454.54.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
