<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smashing Pumpkins Breaking Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Say goodbye to Smashing Pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago-based rock band that was a leader in the alternative
rock revolution of the early 1990s has slumped in sales recently
and will break up at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Billy Corgan called Los Angeles radio station KROQ this
week to announce the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was planning the split even before Smashing Pumpkins
released the album ''Machina/The Machines of God'' in February. He
said the group may release another album from those sessions later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The band is now touring the United States and has concerts
scheduled in Europe. There may be a farewell tour of the U.S. in a
few months.
</P>
<P>
   Corgan said he intends to continue making music but has no
immediate plans. Guitarist James Iha will also stay in music.
Drummer Jimmy Chamberlin wants to pursue a career in auto racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
