<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki bans MTBE in New York; signs acid rain bill  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL GORMLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki continued to try to
follow in the boot steps of Theodore Roosevelt Wednesday by banning
a controversial gasoline additive, battling acid rain and opening a
nature center named for his political hero.
</P>
<P>
   ''The use of MTBE in gasoline has significant environmental
impacts on groundwater,'' Pataki said. ''While today's action is
necessary to protect public health and safeguard the state's
precious water resources, we will continue to fight for federal
action to ban MTBE and identify an acceptable alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Methyl tertiary-butyl ether increases oxygen in gasoline so it
burns ''cleaner'' and reduces air pollution, but it has
increasingly been found in ground and surface water statewide. It
is a particular concern on Long Island because residents there
depend on aquifers for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ''This decision will help protect water quality and public
health on Long Island and across the state,'' said Sarah J. Meyland
of the Citizens Campaign for the Environment.
</P>
<P>
   The effects on the environment of banning MTBE are not that
clear, critics said. The trade-off of banning MTBE, effective in
2004 under the bill signed by Pataki, is that more toxins will be
released into the air from vehicles statewide. That is an
unacceptable and unnecessary trade, said Peter Iwanowicz, director
of environmental health for the American Lung Association's New
York chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a more concerted federal action is needed, one that
will help make cars pollute less without threatening ground water.
Such action, Iwanowicz said, is possible now.
</P>
<P>
   Federal action is also called for because disparities between
states can affect prices at the pump. Suppliers have said that
blending fuel differently to meet a state's standards could
increase prices in that state.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also signed into law a measure that will prohibit New
York state utilities from helping Midwestern companies that exceed
their allowed emissions. The state law closes a loophole in a
federal law that provides for the buying and selling of pollution
''credits'' among industries.
</P>
<P>
   The law was two years in the making because the state Assembly
required that it be applied to pollution credits dating to 1990,
not starting this year as was proposed, said Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky.
</P>
<P>
   The Westchester Democrat, who sponsored the bill in his chamber,
said the difference is the new law will cover about 750,000 tons of
emissions that create acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want any utilities to profit from essentially
unethical behavior whenever the credits were earned,'' said
Brodsky, who wasn't invited to Tuesday's bill-signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The law ''will begin the process of healing New York's
wilderness forests and lakes to the benefit of generations to
come,'' said Neil Woodworth, counsel to the Adirondack Mountain
Club and the New York-New Jersey Trail Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York-based utility companies have a stake in seeing that
similar companies in nearby states follow similar air pollution
standards,'' said Timothy Burke of the Adirondack Council. ''It's
no secret that it's cheaper to produce power at older, dirtier
plants than at the newly equipped, modern facilities that dominate
New York's landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said that unless Congress takes action to better regulate
Midwest emissions that are carried by prevailing winds to fall as
acid rain in New York, the state's utilities will be at a financial
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements were made at the Theodore Roosevelt Nature
Center at Long Island's Jones Beach State Park. Pataki opened the
center with indoor and outdoor exhibits about coastal environments
and wildlife in New York state. It was built with $425,000 in state
and federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just as the life of Theodore Roosevelt has always been a
tremendous source of inspiration to me, it is my hope that this
center will inspire and educate our children and all New Yorkers
about the importance of protecting and preserving the
environment,'' Pataki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 1648 </TRAILER>
