<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Europeans Said Face Obesity  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) -- About half of European adults will be
obese by 2030, partly because of an emerging epidemic of obesity
among children and adolescents, a health researcher said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The growing problem of obesity among European children means
they will face many of the weight-related diseases earlier and die
younger, researchers said at the start of a four-day European
Congress on Obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Heart and circulation problems and the type of diabetes usually
seen in older people are increasingly occurring in European
children -- even 10-year-olds -- because more of them are getting too
fat, said Luc Van Gaal, co-president of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent to 20 percent of European adults are now obese,
compared with about 24 percent of American adults.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not reach yet the U.S. levels, but we are unfortunately
approaching it,'' Van Gaal said.
</P>
<P>
   Practically nobody in Europe is eating an appropriate diet,
according to Philip James, chairman of the International Obesity
Task Force, an independent group of obesity scientists from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have failed to get people into a sane state of thinking
about diet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People are obese if they are so fat that their health is harmed.
It is defined universally by measuring the body mass index, or BMI,
which is calculated by multiplying weight in pounds by 703, then
dividing that result by height in inches squared.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization's threshold for obesity is a body
mass index of 30 or more. People who have a BMI of 25 or more are
considered overweight.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 to 20 percent of European adults are currently obese,
meaning they have a BMI of 30 or more. That figure will grow to as
high as 50 percent in the next 30 years, said Jaap Seidell,
president of the European Association for the Study of Obesity.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people who are obese or overweight, meaning they
have a BMI of 25 or more, will soar to 60-70 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only a minority of people will be able to maintain a healthy
weight in the environment we are creating,'' Seidell said.
</P>
<P>
   Children are getting fatter mainly because their lives are
dramatically different from those of their parents and
grandparents, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Junk food and unhealthy convenience meals are everywhere, while
the computer and television age has kept children sedentary for
longer periods than ever before. Fear of crime also has made some
parents frightened to let their children play outside or cycle to
school.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, 54 percent of 10-year-old girls in Malta and 36
percent of 10-year-old boys in Italy are obese, James said.
</P>
<P>
   Seidell said the food industry spends 1,000 times more on
advertising and marketing fast and convenience foods in Europe and
the United States than the total amount spent by all agencies on
promoting health in the two regions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way in which we structure our society has an impact on the
rate of obesity,'' Seidell said. ''We have to focus on
prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   European health ministers will meet in September at the World
Health Organization to agree upon new food and nutrition strategies
to improve health, and a special European Union conference to
gather expert opinion on nutrition was held in Greece last week.
</P>
<P>
   The EU also is poised to establish the European Food and Public
Health Authority, which will, in part, tackle the prevention of
obesity.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: International Obesity Task Force,
http://www.iotf.org
</P>
<P>
   International Association for the Sutdy of Obesity:
http://iaso.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
