<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakewood rabbi admits tax charge, forfeits Newark housing project  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- An influential Ocean County rabbi on
Wednesday pleaded guilty to a felony tax charge and, as part of a
related civil settlement, forfeited a notorious Newark housing
project.
</P>
<P>
   The company owned by Rabbi Meir N. Hertz that controlled the
Brick Towers Apartments agreed to pay $1 million to the U.S.
Department of Housing and Urban Development and cease operations as
part of the civil settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The company, BTA Properties Inc., also pleaded guilty Wednesday,
admitting it lied to HUD, which gave it millions of dollars in
low-income housing funds, by certifying twice in 1995 that the 298
apartments were ''decent, safe and sanitary.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the 1,000 tenants lived in ''deplorable conditions,''
complaining for years of leaky roofs, balky elevators and sewage
backups, said Paul Aprigliano, director of HUD's enforcement center
for the area.
</P>
<P>
   HUD assumed control of the housing project several months ago,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz resigned last month as executive director of the Lakewood
Housing Authority, a move that was revealed Wednesday to be part of
the settlement. He also accepted a five-year ban on participating
in federal housing programs.
</P>
<P>
   He is still executive director of the Lakewood Township Rental
Assistance Program.
</P>
<P>
   Lakewood Deputy Mayor Marta D. Harrison, a member of the
Township Committee, said she did not know if the township has the
power to remove Hertz, who has an indefinite employment contract.
She said it would be discussed with the four other members of the
governing body.
</P>
<P>
   Other Lakewood officials did not immediately return messages
seeking comment on Hertz.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz, 51, refused to speak to reporters following his guilty
plea. He faces up to three years in prison when sentenced Sept. 25,
but could get probation. He also could be fined up to $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   He remains free on $10,000 bond. With no objection from
prosecutors, U.S. District Judge Mary L. Cooper said Hertz would be
permitted to travel to Israel in July with his family for a son's
bar mitzvah ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz does not preside over a congregation but is a major figure
in Lakewood's large Orthodox Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Edward J. Dauber, said outside court that Hertz
admitted no wrongdoing in connection with his positions at the
housing authority and the rental assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's going to continue with his occupational and
philanthropic activities,'' Dauber said.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to the tax charge, filing a false 1992
return, Hertz admitted he did not include $30,000 he received from
Brick Towers for providing management and security services through
another of his firms, Hertz Management. The money was reported on
his children's returns, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his plea bargain, Hertz agreed to refile his 1992
return, as well as his 1993 return, in which he failed to report
$89,000 of income from Hertz Management by having it put on his
children's returns, court papers showed.
</P>
<P>
   He must pay back taxes, estimated by Assistant U.S. Attorney
Perry A. Carbone at about $20,000, and penalties, before
sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Hertz's Brick Towers Associates owned the apartment project
since 1987, court papers said. HUD has provided BTA with about $2
million a year to be used for upkeep, but not all needed work was
done, Aprigliano said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The building needs at least $6 million to restore it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   HUD's enforcement center has recommended that the Brick Towers
tenants be moved, Aprigliano said.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made on relocation, said Sandi Abadinsky, a
HUD spokeswoman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
