<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman to chair new commission on health of America's oceans  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, who gets
mixed grades from a coastal protection group for her stewardship of
the state's coastline, took the helm Wednesday of a new commission
that will assess the health of America's oceans.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Oceans Commission, formed by the Pew Charitable Trusts,
will spend 18 months studying issues like pollution, overfishing,
coastal development and the health of marine life.
</P>
<P>
   The commission expects that lawmakers will be interested in its
recommendations despite the fact that it was formed by a nonprofit
group.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do a credible job, then I think whoever is president and
whoever is in the Congress will want to pay attention to the report
of this commission,'' said panel vice chairman Leon Panetta, former
White House chief of staff to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking via telephone from Trenton, Whitman, the panel's
chairman, told reporters in Washington that the commission will
''gather the best scientific advice available'' before deciding
what to recommend, and to whom.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an issue that is going to require the cooperation of
government and the private sector, as well as the public in their
everyday life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With Whitman as governor, New Jersey has won praise from
environmental groups for restricting ocean dumping of silt dredged
from harbors and waterways. Cindy Zipf, executive director of New
Jersey-based Clean Ocean Action, has said that New Jersey leads the
nation in developing environmentally responsible alternatives to
dumping.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 agreement closed the so-called ''mud dump'' located 6
miles off Sandy Hook. Only clean material, as defined by the
government, can now be dumped at the site, as a means to bury
contaminated material already there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clean Ocean Action has criticized Whitman of late for not
joining the group in fighting the federal government over its
definition of ''clean.'' The group is particularly angry at the
Whitman administration for agreeing to a project that will dump up
to 310,000 tons of silt dredged from the Raritan River.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman spokeswoman Jayne O'Connor said federal environmental
officials found the Raritan River material to be ''category one,''
or clean, thus leaving the administration little choice but to
concur that it meets the standards of the 1996 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But Kristen Milligan, staff scientist for Clean Ocean Action,
said: ''It's ironic that (Whitman) will be leading this national
commission when she's not engaged in current New Jersey
ocean-protection issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Whitman and Panetta, the panel's 15 other members
represent conservation groups, industry, fishermen and the science
community.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is designed in part as a successor to the Stratton
Commission, which issued a report in 1969 that led to the creation
of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and passage
of the Coastal Zone Management Act of 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are convinced that the ever-deepening ocean crisis requires
an independent and comprehensive reexamination of basic issues in
marine policy,'' said Rebecca Rimel, president of the Pew
Charitable Trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Panetta said there is a growing consensus among scientists on
five ''principle threats'' to marine life -- pollution, coastal
development, fishing, climate change, and the introduction of
nonnative species when ships discharge ballast in bays and harbors.
</P>
<P>
   There is no consensus on solutions, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 1750 </TRAILER>
