<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Up 106; Dow Up 113  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Buyers returned to the stock market Wednesday,
helping the Nasdaq composite index snap a five-day losing streak as
investors sought bargains among blue-chip technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   After a rocky first half to the session, buyers stepped in on
the sense that many well-established stocks have fallen far enough,
analysts said. Volume was robust, ending a two-week long drought.
</P>
<P>
   But the interest rate worries that drove investors to the
sidelines are still in place, leaving the recovery vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite rose 106.06 to close at 3,270.61. Earlier
in the day, the Nasdaq had been down as much as 121 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also bounced back from early
declines and finished up 113.08 at 10,535.35.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were higher, too. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 rose 25.19 to 1,399.05, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies rose 2.73 to 461.74.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors bought stocks because they believed a
five-day decline that knocked 15 percent off the Nasdaq's value
left many stocks at bargain prices. Steep, steady selling in the
past few sessions has wiped away nearly all of the spectacular
gains the Nasdaq achieved between early November and early March.
</P>
<P>
   From an emotional standpoint, many investors were simply tired
of selling, said Scott Bleier, chief investment strategist at Prime
Charter Ltd. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors' fear has led to miserable market action,'' he said.
''Today, that fear finally reached a pessimistic crescendo that
allowed the Nasdaq to put in a bottom and move higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq volume reached 2.05 billion shares by the close of the
regular trading session -- its busiest day in more than a month.
Among the first stocks to benefit: the largest, best-capitalized
technology companies, which some see as a safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems rose 4 37/64 to 55[ and Applied Materials rose 6
9/16 to 78 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have borne the brunt of investors' worries
over rising rates, which are expected to cut into corporate
profits. Many investors have determined that technology stocks,
still among the most expensive issues on the market, are too highly
priced given the weakening outlook for profits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors proved willing to reward technology companies
that are performing well. Intuit rose 8 to 35 1/16 after releasing
an upbeat profit report.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Intel gained 7{ to 117] after releasing its Pentium III
microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Airline stocks drew the most interest Wednesday after UAL, the
parent company of United Airlines, said it is buying US Airways for
$4.3 billion in cash. In addition to the cash payment, UAL will
assume $7.3 billion in debt and aircraft operating leases. That
heavy debt load pared UAL shares 7 3/16 to 53 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   But US Airways shares soared 22 11/16 to 49. Meanwhile, news of
the merger enlivened the rest of the airline sector, lifting shares
of regional airlines that are also seen as takeover targets.
America West rose 2 13/16 to 18 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Larger airlines that are perceived as potential buyers slipped.
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, fell 2 9/16 to 30 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Banking stocks continued a surprising winning streak. Those
stocks are traditionally viewed as most vulnerable to rising
interest rates, which can shrink lending volume and cut into the
value of fixed holdings.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, shares of many financial companies have
thrived. Analysts said some stocks were sold off too steeply in
recent months. Robert Robbins, chief investment strategist at The
Robinson-Humphrey Co. Inc. of Atlanta, said the sector's good
health indicates that the overall market remains fairly strong.
</P>
<P>
   ''For financial stocks to be advancing in the context of a bull
market is phenomenal,'' he said. ''That tells me that there's no
fundamental economic problem hurting stocks right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America rose 3 9/16 to 56[, and Mellon Financial rose 2
3/16 to 38 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers across the board,
underscoring the fragility of the rally. Decliners led by a 10-to-9
margin on the New York Stock Exchange and by a 3-to-2 margin on the
Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.37 billion shares, compared with 1.03
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.7 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 1.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
