<HEADLINE> Dentists reach agreement with state on Medicaid fees  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A federal magistrate signed an agreement
Wednesday ending a dispute between the state and the Dental Society
and resulting in higher fees for dentists treating Medicaid
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will provide $573 million more in Medicaid dental fees
over the next four years and should reverse what the executive
director of the Dental Society, Roy Lasky, called the ''collapse''
of the state's dental Medicaid system.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some areas of the state, currently no dentists will accept
Medicaid reimbursement,'' said Dr. Bertram Bildner, president of
the Dental Society. ''Patients are relegated to seek emergency care
from hospitals or to travel to neighboring counties or out-of-state
for their dental treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   The 13,000-member Dental Society filed suit in February 1999
claiming that dental Medicaid rates have not appreciably increased
in New York for three decades. That, in turn, had left more than 1
million low-income New York children without access to important
dental health care, the suit claimed.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to the two sides argue the case in court,
District Judge Norman Mordue in Syracuse had urged the parties to
try to negotiate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The new fee schedule, which goes into effect June 1, calls for
the current dentists' reimbursement for a basic examination or an
adult to go from $10 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   A typical four-picture set of X-rays will increase from $5 to
$20 and a common procedure where a fluoride sealant is applied to a
tooth will go up from $18 to $25.50.
</P>
<P>
   Reimbursement for a crown will increase from $300 to $400, the
same as for dentures.
</P>
<P>
   The old fee schedule only covered 30 percent or less of
dentists' costs for treating Medicaid patients, said Dental Society
spokeswoman Judi Schub.
</P>
<P>
   Lasky said the fee scheduled had been allowed to deteriorate
under Govs. Hugh Carey, Mario Cuomo and George Pataki. But he
credited Pataki with being willing to improve reimbursement rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Dental Society sued when Carey was governor for higher fees,
though the settlement of $10 million at that time was
''microscopic'' compared with the ''earth-shattering'' settlement
finalized on Wednesday, Lasky said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, $132 million more will be available in
Medicaid funds to dentists for the period from June 1 to March 31,
2001. It also calls for Pataki to appoint a committee with members
from the Dental Society and the Health Department to study the new
fee structure, how it is affecting the availability of services to
Medicaid patients and to recommend further changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be an innovative and creative approach,'' Schub said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was signed Wednesday by U.S. Magistrate David
Homer in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Department could provide no information about
the $573 million agreement Wednesday nor comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the new 2000-01 state budget, the state also raised
fees for physicians and other medical professionals treating
Medicaid patients. Advocates for the poor said the old fee schedule
was deterring many doctors from opening their doors to Medicaid
patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 1903 </TRAILER>
