<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrat Probe Stories Conflict  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An FBI official and a prosecutor gave Congress
conflicting testimony Wednesday in the ongoing argument between the
bureau and the Justice Department over the campaign fund-raising
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The latest dispute, before a Senate subcommittee, concerned
whether prosecutor Lee Radek told two FBI officials in 1996 that he
felt pressured because Attorney General Janet Reno's job hinged on
the department's handling of the probe of fund raising for
President Clinton's re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant FBI director Neil Gallagher said the prosecutor told
him he was under ''pressure'' which was ''attributed to the fact
the attorney general's job may hang in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   But Radek testified he never said that: ''It would be a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the December 1996 meeting at FBI headquarters,
director Louis Freeh was pushing for the bureau to be brought into
the fund-raising probe, which Justice was conducting without it.
Freeh was also upset that Reno hadn't sought his views before
rejecting the appointment of an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Freeh repeatedly recommended that an independent
counsel be sought to investigate top Clinton administration
officials in the campaign fund-raising controversy. Reno has
maintained that ''the facts and the law'' dictated her decision
that an independent counsel wasn't warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, suggested that prosecutors feared
an aggressive fund-raising probe would lead to Reno losing her job
as Clinton began his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like the Public Integrity Section at the Justice
Department just dropped the ball,'' Grassley said, referring to the
office headed by Radek.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., pointed to ''the large number
of independent counsels'' sought by Reno as ''substantive proof of
the attorney general's integrity'' in investigating the Clinton
administration when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my gut, I believe in Attorney General Janet Reno,'' Schumer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Radek denied that his work was affected by questions about
Reno's tenure. He clashed with Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who
suggested there was more than enough information to require an
independent counsel investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did my best to administer the law as best I could,'' Radek
said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor acknowledged that he disliked the now-defunct
independent counsel law because of ''the damage I thought it did to
our system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the atmosphere of the campaign-finance probe as ''a
pressure cooker. We were being scrutinized by Congress, the news
media and the attorney general.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the only pressure was ''to do a good job, do it
vigorously and do it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher's account of the meeting corroborated another FBI
official's recollection, as recorded in a 1996 memo by Freeh,
turned over belatedly to Senate investigators and reported by The
Associated Press last week.
</P>
<P>
   According to the memo by Freeh, who was not at the meeting,
then-FBI deputy director William Esposito quoted Radek as saying
''that there was a lot of 'pressure' on him ... regarding this case
because the attorney general's job might hang in the balance (or
words to that effect).''
</P>
<P>
   Radek said he has ''no recollection'' of the meeting in
question, but was sure he would not have linked Reno's job with the
''pressure'' he felt in the campaign finance probe.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who has obtained court appointment of seven independent
counsels, said she never bowed to political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I call it like I see it, regardless of the consequences,'' she
said recently. Reno added she did not recall Freeh briefing her on
Radek's purported remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, legal sources say the Justice Department's campaign
task force found no evidence of wrongdoing regarding more than $1.3
million in donations to Democrats by Loral Corp. chairman Bernard
Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   At a May 2 hearing, Specter described a 1998 memo by
then-Justice Department prosecutor Charles LaBella as saying
President Clinton should be investigated in connection with the
donations. Loral obtained a waiver from the Clinton administration
allowing the company to do satellite business in China.
</P>
<P>
   However, by the time of LaBella's memo, he and the task force
had effectively excused Loral and Schwartz from the probe and
LaBella said there had been only a ''whisp of information'' to
justify the Justice Department's inquiry of Schwartz to begin with,
said legal sources familiar with various internal Justice
Department documents in the fund-raising probe. The Los Angeles
Times earlier this week first reported on the additional
information clearing Schwartz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
