<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In spending blitz, Corzine keeps distance from news media  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- While spending his own wealth on tightly
crafted TV commercials, U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine has been
warily avoiding too much exposure to news reporters and
photographers over whom he has no control.
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic primary opponent, former Gov. Jim Florio, has
taken every chance to draw as much attention as possible from
newspapers and broadcasters. Corzine has done the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his campaign, Corzine this week invited
news reporters to watch him on the stump when he visited a senior
citizens center Monday in one of Trenton's poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the only Corzine events to be broadly publicized
were a handful of staged news conferences at which prominent
officials gave him their endorsement. Events at which news
reporters could watch him spontaneously meeting and talking with
voters have been unpublicized.
</P>
<P>
   He has also refused to accept invitations to appear in debates
to be broadcast on network television, most recently from the Gabe
Pressman show on WNBC-TV in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''The independent press is their one means of getting
consistent, independent coverage to make up their minds who they
want to vote for,'' said Rem Rieder, editor of the American
Journalism Review based at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no law that says he has got to make it easy, but if
(the campaign) is not providing readily accessible information
about where he is going to be, that is reprehensible because voters
really deserve aggressive, independent coverage of a candidate,
particularly when they are being bombarded by so much paid
advertising,'' said Rieder, who was editor of The Times of Trenton
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine denies his campaign staff has been trying to hide him.
He said news reporters have an open invitation to attend and
observe any campaign stops, and have been accommodated for lengthy
one-on-one interviews. He said reporters need only contact his
staff in advance to find out where the campaign might be on any
given day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is just not consistent with the facts. We have never
restricted any of the press. You've been welcome at any of my
speeches. We encourage people to come visit,'' Corzine said.
''People are around me all the time. I had a reporter from New
Republic with me all day (Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   ''I will show you my schedule for weeks and weeks and weeks,''
Corzine said.
</P>
<P>
   But since Monday, Corzine's campaign, which grinds out dozens of
documents to news organization fax machines each day, has not
issued a single advisory about any such campaign activity.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hartmann, retired professor of journalism at Rutgers
University, said there is a big difference between permitting news
reporters to attend events and giving adequate notice about events
that are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never faced anything like this before. Usually people
are vying for free media coverage,'' Hartmann said. ''Usually the
campaign will send out a schedule. This is where the candidate will
be today. ... And you hope that some reporters will come along and
cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   Political and media analysts agree it is strange for any
political candidate to seek something less than maximum exposure.
But when coupled with a spending frenzy bound to shatter national
records, some find Corzine's caginess with the news media
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to have a sugarcoated package, not the unvarnished
version that comes when you have reporters along watching what you
are doing,'' said Rieder.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jim McQueeny, who covered statewide campaigns
as a reporter for The Star-Ledger of Newark in the 1970s, said, ''I
have not seen this in 20 years of New Jersey politics.''
</P>
<P>
   McQueeny said Corzine is revealing a businessman's approach:
Having invested so heavily in his campaign image, he wants to
protect the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine had a brief public-relations problem when it was
revealed last month he had made mob jokes during a meeting with
some Italian-Americans last year. Corzine said he did not recall
the remarks but he apologized for them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   McQueeny said a second mistake like that in the days leading to
the June 6 primary could literally do millions of dollars of
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you think that after investing $20 million to put forth the
best portrayal possible, that you want a $30,000-a-year reporter
covering some chance encounter to jeopardize that image,'' he said.
''One unfortunate street encounter can undo everything that $20
million in TV tried to do for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann said he was inclined to disagree. He suspected rather
that the Corzine campaign was just so fixed on commercial TV
spending and the views of strategic consultants, there is little
interest in newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   ''They maybe don't give a damn. I don't know if it is so much
that they are worried that he will say something wrong, or that
something negative will come out of it,'' Hartmann said. ''It would
say to me that maybe candidates are getting to the point where they
are just not interested in the free media.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-24-00 2015 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000524.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Proposes Arsenic Water Limits  </HEADLINE>
By BART JANSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency proposed
Wednesday to reduce the limit for arsenic allowed in drinking water
to one-tenth the current standard in an effort to reduce cancer
risks for 22 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The agency proposed to reduce the arsenic allowed in drinking
water from 50 parts per billion to 5 parts per billion. The
announcement came two weeks after an environmental group, the
Natural Resources Defense Council, filed a federal lawsuit to force
the White House to allow the agency to propose the long-awaited
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will continue to take actions to protect public health by
strengthening existing standards when necessary, as we are doing
today,'' said Carol Browner, EPA administrator.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 6,600 water systems nationwide serving at least
22.5 million people would need to upgrade their systems to meet the
standard.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's certainly a very good start,'' said Erik Olson, a senior
lawyer for the environmental group, which advocated an even lower
standard of 3 parts per billion. ''If this rule goes final, which
we sure hope it will, millions of Americans will have water that is
safer to drink and have a lower history of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials warned the new standard could increase
household water costs up to $100 a year for customers largely in
the rural Southwest and pockets of New England where arsenic levels
are highest.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as the impact on small systems, it can be brutal,''
said Doug Marsano, spokesman for The American Water Works
Association based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is asking for public comments for 90 days about lowering
the standard. After reviewing the comments, a final rule could be
put in place by early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If a lower standard is set, large water systems serving 10,000
people or more would have three years to make improvements and
smaller systems would have five years. About 95 percent of the
systems failing to meet the proposed standard are small systems.
</P>
<P>
   Water industry representatives, who agree that the current
arsenic standard is too high, are pushing for a standard of 10
parts per billion, which would match the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers working for the water association estimated it would
cost $600 million a year to meet an arsenic standard of 10 parts
per billion in water, after spending $5 billion on new equipment.
The cost would more than double to $1.4 billion a year after $14
billion in capital costs, to meet a standard of 5 parts per
billion, the association said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reduce arsenic drinking water followed a National
Academy of Sciences report in 1999 that found arsenic in drinking
water causes bladder, lung and skin cancer, and might cause kidney
and liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Geological Survey map of counties with high
arsenic levels: http://co.water.usgs.gov/trace/arsenic
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-24-00 2049 </TRAILER>
