<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family members still awaiting identifications of loved ones  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER NEWTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- Mourning families of the 19 victims of
a weekend plane crash were still awaiting formal confirmation from
coroners that the bodies of their loved ones had been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The final word from investigators would allow friends and
relatives to begin making funeral arrangements and help bring some
closure to the tragedy, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want to get to a point where we can just reflect,''
said Elizabeth Mates, a friend of 63-year-old Joan Kunkle, who was
killed on the flight. ''All I can think of is her laying up there
waiting for the autopsy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an airport conference room Tuesday, families were told by
National Transportation Safety Board investigators that definitive
answers as to what may have caused the plane to have a double
engine failure could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors from several community and religious groups prepared
them Wednesday for an even more disheartening possibility: They may
never know.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to suggest that families not concentrate just on
getting answers about why the plane may have crashed,'' said Wilma
Edwards, a counselor with the American Red Cross who spoke with
family members. ''Often times, even after the answers come, they
just raise even more questions. We encourage them to mourn and
celebrate their loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Counselors said that most families were still dealing with the
shock and second-guessing the everyday decisions that led their
respective loved ones to head to Atlantic City, N.J., for a weekend
gambling trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of the process is accepting that these types of things
never make any sense,'' said the Rev. Paul Dickinson, who counseled
family members Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now a lot of people are still thinking 'She would still
be alive if only I had told her not to take the trip,''' Dickinson
said. ''Life just doesn't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, coroners spent the day at an airport hangar
attempting to identify victims using dental records, medical
records and family photos.
</P>
<P>
   There was some question as to whether the final body had been
removed from the crash scene, and local coroners were unavailable
for comment Wednesday. National Transportation Safety Board
officials also did not immediately return calls by The Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB officials on Wednesday directed the continued removal of
the wreckage from the mountainside. Tuesday, construction workers
retrieved the plane's engines and propellers and prepared to send
them to manufacturer assembly plants for study.
</P>
<P>
   Crash investigators hope a computer-enhanced examination of two
recordings of the final conversation between air traffic
controllers and pilots will yield hidden clues as to why a charter
plane crashed in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigator Frank Hilldrup said he also did not know how
long it would take for the last of the wreckage to be removed,
ending the on-site investigation. He said a final NTSB report could
take up to a year to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe they did have a general outline of what
happened just before the Executive Airlines twin-engine turboprop
crashed in the rain nine miles south of the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton
International Airport late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots declared an emergency soon after missing their first
approach of an airport runway, according to investigators. Just
before the second approach, the pilots said they had lost both
engines.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers began providing information about the
terrain and elevation after radar indicated the plane was flying at
about 2,000 feet above sea level, considerably lower than the
minimum safe altitude, Hilldrup said. The crash site was 1,765 feet
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Transportation Safety Board:
http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
